Amount of 2-methylacetoacetic acid in the urine above upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 2-methylacetoacetic acid level
Amount of 3-hydroxypropionic acid in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 3-hydroxypropionic acid level
Amount of 2-methylcitric acid in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 2-methylcitric acid level
Amount of 4-hydroxyisovaleric acid in urine above upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 4-hydroxyisovaleric acid level

Amount of 2-hydroxy-3-methylvaleric acid in the urine above the upper limit of normal. 2-Hydroxy-3-methylpentanoic acid or 2-hydroxy-3-methylvaleric acid (HMVA) is an organic acid generated by L-isoleucine metabolism.
Elevated urine 2-hydroxy-3-methylvaleric acid level

Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of the shoulder joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.
Shoulder contracture

Lack of the full expected passive range of flexion of the shoulder joint (Shoulder flexion puts the arms from a resting position at one's sides to straight above the head; thus, with shoulder extension contracture it is not possible to raise the arms above the head fully).
Shoulder extension contracture

Movement in the sagittal plane that increases the angle of the thumb joint (straightens the joint); motion involving posterior bending of the vertebral column or returning to the upright position from a flexed position.
Thumb extension contracture
A myxoma (benign soft tissue neoplasm characterized by the presence of spindle and stellate cells, lobulated growth pattern, and myxoid stroma formation) localized in the tongue.
Tongue myxoma
A structural abnormality of the knee joint or surrounding structures.
Abnormal knee morphology
A functional anomaly of the knee joint.
Abnormal knee physiology

Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of the knee joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.
Knee contracture
A type of knee joint contracture in which the knee lacks full expected flexion, such that the upper and lower leg cannot be brought together.
Knee extension contracture
A structural anomaly of the ankle.
Abnormal ankle morphology
A functional anomaly of the ankle.
Abnormal ankle physiology

Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of a toe joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.
Toe joint contracture
A type of toe joint contracture in which the joint lacks full expected flexion, so that the two bony segments on either side of their connecting joint cannot be brought together.
Extension contracture of toe
Ankle contracture
Forefoot pronation contracture
Forefoot supination contracture
Forefoot adduction contracture

Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of a finger joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.
Finger joint contracture
A type of finger joint contracture in which the joint lacks full expected flexion, so that the two bony segments on either side of their connecting joint cannot be brought together.
Extension contracture of finger
Amount of telethonin protein expression in muscle tissue below lower limit of normal. Telethonin is a 19-kDa sarcomeric protein, localized to the Z-disc of skeletal and cardiac muscles.
Reduced muscle telethonin level
Concentration or activity of an enzyme is above or below the limits of normal.
Abnormal enzyme concentration or activity
Concentration or activity of an enzyme is above or below the limits of normal in liver tissue.
Abnormal liver enzyme activity or concentration
Activity of urocanase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic urocanase activity

Reduced hydrolysis (splitting of a bond and the addition of the hydrogen anion of water) of the sulfuric ester linkage in the molecule of cerebroside sulfate, possibly leading to accumuation of cerebroside sulfate.
Impaired cerebroside sulfate hydrolysis

Diminished enzyme activity of peroxisomal glutaryl-CoA oxidase, an enzyme that metabolizes glutaryl-CoA (a metabolite of L-lysine, L-hydroxy-lysine and L-tryptophan) by dehydrogenation to glutaconyl-CoA directly followed by decarboxylation of this to crotonyl-CoA.
Reduced peroxisomal glutaryl-CoA oxidase activity

Diminished activity of the enzyme sterol 27-hydroxylase, which participates in the degradation of cholesterol to bile acid. Sterol 27-hydroxylase catalyzes the first step in the normal oxidation of the steroid side chain, converting cholesterol, as well as different 7a-hydroxylated cholesterol metabolites, to 27-oxygenated steroids.
Reduced sterol 27-hydroxylase activity
Diminished activity of the enzyme Short-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (SCAD), a key enzyme of fatty acid beta-oxidation that catalyzes the first step in mitochondrial beta-oxidation of fatty acids.
Reduced short-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase activity

Diminished activity of the enzyme 3-phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase (PGDH), which catalyzes the first step in the pathway by converting D-3-phosphoglycerate (PGA), an intermediate in glycolysis, to phosphohydroxypyruvate concomitant with the reduction of NAD+.
Reduced 3-phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase activity
Increase in length of mitochondria.
Elongated mitochondria
Activity of methionine adenosyltransferase in the liver below the lower limit of normal. Note that there are multiple methionine adenosyltransferase isoezymes.
Reduced hepatic methionine adenosyltransferase activity
Degeneration and loss of neurons in the substantia nigra of the brain.
Substantia nigra dopaminergic neuron loss
A lipoma that is located within a muscle.
Intramuscular lipoma
Dilated blood vessels on the skin.
Cutaneous telangiectasia
Aromatase activity outside of the normal range.
Abnormal aromatase activity
Enzyme activity of aromatase above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated aromatase activity
Enzyme activity of aromatase below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced aromatase activity
A form of amyloidosis that is located in the cornea.
Corneal amyloidosis
Any structural anomaly of the keratinocyte. The keratinocyte is the major cell type of the epidermis and is responsible for generating the protective barrier.
Abnormal keratinocyte morphology
Increased number of vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles that areempty of cytoplasm, lined with a membrane, and filled with fluid) in keratinocytes.
Keratinocyte vacuolization
An adenocarcinoma that arises from the parotid gland.
Parotid gland adenocarcinoma
Cellular inflammation, vessel destruction, and tissue necrosis of the blood vessels of the lung.
Pulmonary vasculitis
Activity of D-glycerate kinase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic D-glycerate kinase activity
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages in a lymph node.
Lymph-node hemophagocytosis
Underdevelopment of the upper branch of the pubis bone (inferior pubic ramus).
Superior pubic ramus hypoplasia
A rare benign mullerian mixed tumor of the uterus composed of benign epithelial and mesenchymal components.
Uterine adenofibroma

A benign malformation of the lung that includes an abnormal mixture of tissue components such as cartilage, epithelium, fat, or muscle which are common to the lung but without preservation of the organ architecture.
Pulmonary hamartoma
An abnormal histological finding characterized by an increase in the cross-section area of peripheral nerve axons (up to 20-25 micrometers in diameter).
Peripheral axonal distension
Concentration or activity of alpha mannosidase below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating alpha-mannosidase activity
A structural anomaly of the hepatocyte, which is the main cell type that makes up the liver perncyhma. Hepatocytes are usually binucleated and appear as sheets in the liver tissue.
Abnormal hepatocyte morphology
Accumulation of dark, coarsely granular pigment localized in lysosomes of centrilobular hepatocytes.
Hepatic melanin-like lysosomal pigmentation
Activity of the enzyme uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase (UROD; EC 4.1.1.37) below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase activity
Activity of the enzyme heme oxygenase below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced heme oxygenase activity
The presence of enlarged and swollen neurons that lack Nissl bodies (the rough endoplasmic reticulum-achromasia refers to neurons that lack Nissl bodies) in the cortex of the brain.
Swollen achromatic neurons in the cerebral cortex
Presence of vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles that areempty of cytoplasm, lined with a membrane, and filled with fluid) in hepatocytes, which normally rarely contain vacuoles.
Vacuolated hepatocytes

An abnormality of oocyte maturation characterized by the inability of oocytes to form pronuclei after in vitro fertilization procedures. Oocytes normally show two pronuclei 17 to 20 hours after in vitro insemination.
Lack of oocyte pronucleus formation
A type of skin tumor that initially presents as a reddish macule and subsequently becomes papular, enlarged, ulcerated and ultimately heals leaving pitted scars.
Self-healing squamous epithelioma
Concentration of pristanic acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating pristanic acid concentration
Rounded or oval structures that appeared brown on hematoxylin and eosin and red on the modified Gomori trichrome stain.
Sarcoplasmic bodies
Elevated CSF hydroxyproline concentration

Concentration of cystine in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal. Cystine is sulfur-containing amino acid obtained by the oxidation of two cysteine molecules which are then linked via a disulfide bond.
Reduced CSF cystine concentration
Activity of the enzyme beta-mannosidase outside normal limits. Beta-mannosidase is a lysosomal enzyme that catabolizes oligosaccharides.
Abnormal circulating beta-mannosidase activity
Activity of the enzyme beta-mannosidase above the upper limit of normal. Beta-mannosidase is a lysosomal enzyme that catabolizes oligosaccharides.
Elevated circulating beta-mannosidase activity
Activity of the enzyme alpha-L-fucosidase below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating alpha-L-fucosidase activity
Activity of the enzyme alpha-L-fucosidase in the blood circulation outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal circulating alpha-L-fucosidase activity
Activity of the enzyme alpha-L-fucosidase above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating alpha-L-fucosidase activity
Increased concentration of S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine concentration
Concentration S-adenosyl-L-methionine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating S-adenosyl-L-methionine concentration

Malignant hyperthermia that is characterized by exercise-induced life-threatening hyperthermia with a body temperature over 40 degrees C and signs of encephalopathy ranging from confusion to convulsions or coma. Incidence increases with rising ambient temperature and relative humidity. Manifestations may include rhabdomyolysis (presenting with myalgia, muscle weakness, and myoglobinuria), tachycardia, and in severe cases multiorgan failure.
Exercise-triggered malignant hyperthermia

Malignant hyperthermia that is characterized by a rapid increase in temperature to 39-42 degrees C in response to inhalational anesthetics such as halothane or to muscle relaxants such as succinylcholine.
Anesthesic-triggered malignant hyperthermia
Concentration of argininosuccinic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF argininosuccinic acid concentration
Concentration of aspartylglucosamine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF aspartylglucosamine concentration
Concentration of alpha-oxoadipic acid in the blood above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating alpha-oxoadipic acid concentration
A deviation from the normal range of a metabolite in red blood cells.
Abnormal erythrocyte metabolite concentration

Concentration of glutathione in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal. Glutathione (GSH) is an important redox active biomolecule critical in the maintenance and regulation of cellular and organismal health.
Reduced erythrocyte glutathione concentration
Concentration of sarcosine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF sarcosine concentration
Concentration of methionine in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced CSF methionine concentration
Concentration of homoarginine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating homoarginine concentration
The concentration of formiminoglutamic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary formiminoglutamic acid level
Concentration of proline in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF proline concentration
Level of S-sulfocysteine high in urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary S-sulfocysteine level
Concentration of S-sulfocysteine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating S-sulfocysteine concentration
Abnormal increase in the number of Sertoli cells in the testis.
Sertoli cell hyperplasia
The presence of an infectious agent in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
CSF infectious agent
Mycobacterium present in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). This feature can be ascertained by CSF microscopy.
CSF mycobacteria
Detection of a fungal organism (such as candida or coccidioides) in the blood stream.
Fungal bloodstream infection
Enlarged lymph node located just above the clavicle (collarbone).
Supraclavicular lymphadenopathy
Enlarged lymph node located in the inguinal region (groin).
Inguinal lymphadenopathy
Enlarged lymph node located in the axillary region (armpit).
Axillary lymphadenopathy

Murphy's sign is elicited in patients with acute cholecystitis by asking the patient to take in and hold a deep breath while palpating the subcostal region. In practice, Murphy's sign is performed by palpating the subcostal region during inspiration. If pain is elicited and the patient suddenly stops their inspiratory effort, a positive Murphy's sign has been elicited.
Positive Murphy sign
Vomiting whereby the vomit has the color of bile, yellowish-green.
Bilious emesis
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID).
Ameliorated by NSAID
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to a medication or other substance.
Fetal exposure history

A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to barbiturate medications such as phenobarbital. Barbiturates are used medically as anxiolytics, hypnotics, and anticonvulsants.
Fetal barbiturate exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to narcotic medications such as morphine or codeine. Narcotics are used medically to treat moderate or severe pain.
Fetal narcotic exposure
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by administration of ethosuximide. Ethosuximide is most often used to treat absence seizures.
Ameliorated by ethosuximide
Lower than normal amount of extracellular matrix protein 1 (ECM1) in the epidermis.
Reduced epidermal extracellular matrix protein 1 protein expression
Neurofibroma categorized according to the anatomical site of origin.
Neurofibroma by anatomical location
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the tongue.
Tongue neurofibroma
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the heart.
Cardiac neurofibroma
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the stomach.
Gastric neurofibroma
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the kidney.
Renal neurofibroma
Accumulation of a poorly branched and poorly spherical amylopectin-like glycogen (polyglucosan) in muscle fibers.
Muscle fiber polyglucosan inclusion bodies
Abnormal structure of the rete ridges (also known as rete pegs), which are downward projections of epithelium surrounding the connective tissue papillae in between the dermal papillae.
Abnormal rete ridge morphology
Increased length of the rete rdiges of the epidermis.
Rete ridge elongation
Accumulation of monoclonal CD1a-positive Langerhans cells in the bronchioles and alveolar interstitium that can cause damage to the lungs.
Pulmonary Langerhans cell histiocytosis
Flattening of a curve in the spine in the lumbar (lower back) region.
Lumbar hypolordosis

Battle sign is bruising over the mastoid process that is typically the result of head trauma. It is retroauricular or mastoid ecchymosis that is typically the result of head trauma. Battle sign typically requires significant head trauma and may indicate significant internal injury to the brain and not just the posterior cranial vault or mastoid.
Battle sign
Reduced anterioposterior dimension of the skull base.
Decreased skull base length
A visual disturbance in which objects in the visual field appear to oscillate (jump, jiggle, vibrate).
Oscillopsia
The frequency with which the eye is blinked is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased blink rate
A deviation from the normal frequency of blinking the eye.
Abnormal blink rate
The frequecy with which the eye is blinked is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated blink rate
Sputum contains pus.
Purulent sputum
The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of hyperthyroidism during the corresponding pregnancy.
Maternal hyperthyroidism
Applies to an abnormality that affects the perineum (the region of skin between the genitals and the anus).
Perineal
History of exposure to gadolinium, a contrast medium often used for magnetic resonance imaging.
Gadolinium exposure
Excretion of pus (purulent discharge) from the opening of the parotid duct.
Purulent parotid gland drainage
Obstipation is the inability to pass either stool or flatus (gas).
Obstipation
Vomiting following a coughing spell.
Posttussive emesis
Vasculitis categorized according to the anatomical site where the finding is localized.
Vasculitis by anatomical site
Vasculitis categorized according to type of histological abnormality.
Vasculitis by histology
A type of vasculitis characterized by the presence of debris of neutrophils within the blood vessel walls.
Leukocytoclastic vasculitis
Accumulation of lipid droplets in small-bowel enterocytes
A pericardial friction rub is a grating, to-and-fro sound that occurs in phase with the heart sounds.
Pericardial friction rub
Muscular vasculitis
Any deviation from the normal amount of staining of succinate dehydrogenase in skeletal muscle tissue.
Abnormal muscle succinate dehydrogenase staining
Increased muscle succinate dehydrogenase staining
Decreased muscle succinate dehydrogenase staining
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the small intestine.
Small intestinal hamartoma

Pyriform spermatozoa consist of a normally shaped acrosomal structure which can be normal in size or enlarged, while the post-acrosomal region shows severe elongation and an acute narrowing to the posterior end, ending in about the same thickness as the connecting mid-piece.
Pyriform sperm head

Excess residual cytoplasm is associated with abnormal spermatozoa produced from a defective spermiation process. This abnormal excess cytoplasm should not be confused with more physiological cytoplasmic residues that can be observed in direct microscopy of the ejaculate but not in dried, fixed and stained morphology smears.
Excess residual spermatozoal cytoplasm
Subsarcolemmal, eosinophilic glass-like regions within the cytoplasm of cardiomyocytes.
Cardiomyocyte hyaline bodies
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages observed in the liver.
Hepatic hemophagocytosis
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages observed in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
CSF hemophagocytosis
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages observed in the spleen.
Splenic hemophagocytosis

The presence of multiple granulomas in the urinary bladder as based on pathological examination. Granulomas are small 0.5 to 2 mm collections of modified macrophages called epithelioid cells usually surrounded by lymphocytes.
Urinary bladder granulomatosis
Death of keratinocytes in the epidermis layer of the skin, which generally manifests as extensive exfoliation (separation of the epidermis from the underlying dermis).
Epidermal necrosis
Applied to a sign or symptom that is aggravated by (or made more painful by) bending of a limb or joint.
Exacerbated by flexion
The presence of blood in tears.
Hemolacria
A perception that an object is in contact with the eye.
Corneal foreign body sensation
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the buttock (round fleshy area at the lower rear area of a human trunk).
Buttock pain
A perception that an object located in the vagina.
Vaginal foreign body sensation
Attacks of breathlessness that occur at night and may awaken the sleeping patient.
Paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the eyelid.
Eyelid pain

Abnormality of a sperm function including protection of paternal DNA, traversing the female reproductive tract, oocyte localisation, penetration of the zona pellucida, oocyte activation and centriole deposition.
Abnormal sperm physiology

Reduction in size of the acrosome below the lower limit of normal. The acrosome is a unique membranous organelle located over the anterior part of the sperm nucleus. According to the World Health Organization criteria, the acrosome must be clearly visible, comprising approximately 40-70 percent of the sperm head.
Small acrosomal area
The proportion of sperm cells whose flagella is sharply curved or has a sharp angle is above normal limits.
Bent sperm flagella

Spermiation failure is indicated by apparently normal spermiogenesis, but the presence of retained Sd2 spermatids in stages III-V of human spermatogenesis, whereas maturation arrest is indicated by a lack of late Sd1 and Sd2 spermatids in the epithelium.
Spermiation failure

A morphological abnormality visible upon biopsy of the germinal epithelium of the testis in which the cellularity of the germinal epithelium is reduced in general, so that all stages of germ cells (spermatogonia, spermatocytes, and spermatids) are present but reduced in number. This term applies to biopsies with some tubules showing diminished amounts of qualitatively complete spermatogenesis in combination with a vast majority of tubules that lack germ cells.
Hypospermatogenesis
Formation of a sheet of tissue by coagulum of exudate over the conjunctiva of the eye that if removed leaves behind a denuded bleeding surface.
Conjunctival membrane

A type of oligozoospermia characterized by a total number of more than zero but less than 2 million sperm in the ejaculate or a concentration of more than zero but less than one million sperm per milliliter.
Extreme oligozoospermia

A type of oligozoospermia characterized by a total number of more than 30 but less than 39 million sperm in the ejaculate or a concentration of more than 10 but less than 15 million sperm per milliliter.
Mild oligozoospermia

A type of oligozoospermia characterized by a total number of more than 10 but less than 29 million sperm in the ejaculate or a concentration of more than 5 but less than 10 million sperm per milliliter.
Moderate oligozoospermia

A type of oligozoospermia characterized by a total number of more than 2 but less than 10 million sperm in the ejaculate or a concentration of more than 1 but less than 5 million sperm per milliliter.
Severe oligozoospermia
The presence of a nodule (small rounded lump of tissue) in the iris.
Iris nodule
A type of iris nodule consisting of inflammatory cell precipitates which lie at the pupillary margin.
Koeppe nodules
A type of iris nodule consisting of inflammatory cell precipitates which lie on the iris surface.
Bussaca nodules
Abnormal CSF ion concentration
Concentration of copper in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased CSF copper concentration

Diffuse lymphoid hyperplasia (DLH) describes the pathological entity that lies between follicular bronchiolitis and lymphocytic interstitial pneumonia (LIP). It is pathologically characterized by a diffuse peribronchiolar proliferation of hyperplastic lymphoid follicles (BALT), extended along the lymphatics to involve the interlobular septa and pleura. Unlike LIP, DHL does not show uniform involvement of the alveolar septa.
Diffuse pulmonary lymphoid hyperplasia
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with a steroid medication such as prednisone.
Ameliorated by steroid medication
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by administration of levothyroxin (thyroid hormone).
Triggered by levothyroxin exposure
A decreased amount of laminin alpha-2 chain in muscle tissue. This feature can be shown by immunohistochemistry or Western blotting of muscle tissue.
Reduced muscle laminin alpha-2 chain staining
Abnormal thickening of of the outer layer (cortex) of the adrenal gland due to fibrosis.
Adrenal cortical sclerosis
Concentration or activity of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate aldolase in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic fructose-1,6-phosphate aldolase activity
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the pancreas.
Pancreatic hamartoma
A benign liver neoplasm composed of fat, vascular, and smooth muscle elements.
Liver angiomyolipoma
A lipoma that is located within a the heart.
Cardiac lipoma
Accumulation of a poorly branched and poorly spherical amylopectin-like glycogen (polyglucosan) in peripheral nerve fibers.
Peripheral nerve polyglucosan inclusion bodies
Accumulation of a poorly branched and poorly spherical amylopectin-like glycogen (polyglucosan) in myocardial tissue.
Cardiac polyglucosan accumulation
A benign cystic neoplasm of the kidney.
Cystic nephroma
Elastic fibers not demonstrable in skin biopsy.
Absent dermal elastic fibers
Splitting of the skin (cell-cell adhesion of keratinocytes) localized to the interface between the stratum corneum and stratum granulosum layers of the epidermis.
Cleavage at junction of stratum corneum and stratum granulosum

An abnormal bone marrow finding characterized by many poorly circumscribed and occasionally confluent lymphoid nodules. The nodules contain small and uniform lymphocytes with rounded nuclei, clumped chromatin, and without prominent nucleoli.
Lymphoid hyperplasia

Lack of lamellar bodies (LBs) inthe epidermis. LBs are specialized organelles that contain pro-barrier lipids imparting a fully lamellar internal structure, but also other cargoes such as enzymes (lipid metabolizing and proteolytic), enzyme inhibitors, and antimicrobial peptides.
Absence of epidermal lamellar bodies

The presence of multiple granulomas in the gastrointestinal tract (Pylorus, esophagus, jejunum, ileum, cecum, rectum, perirectal area, esophagus) as based on pathological examination. Granulomas are small 0.5 to 2 mm collections of modified macrophages called epithelioid cells usually surrounded by lymphocytes.
Gastrointestinal granulomatosis

Increased size of sperm vacuoles, which are surface concavities typically located at the the tip or middle area of sperm heads. According to the WHO Laboratory Manual for the Examination and Processing of Human Semen, sperm head vacuoles are considered abnormal when exceeding 20% of the cross-sectional area of the head. Vacuoles are found in almost all samples with normal sperm morphology; this term applies if the proportion of sperm with abnormally large vacuoles is above the upper limit of normal.
Enlarged sperm head vacuole
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the ureter.
Ureteral hamartoma
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to methimazole.
Fetal methimazole exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to procarbazine.
Fetal procarbazine exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to fluorouracil.
Fetal fluorouracil exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to cytarabine.
Fetal cytarabine exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to tetracycline.
Fetal tetracycline exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to quinine.
Fetal quinine exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to cyclophosphamide.
Fetal cyclophosphamide exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to metronidazole.
Fetal metronidazole exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to phenobarbital.
Fetal phenobarbital exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to phenytoin.
Fetal phenytoin exposure
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are located at or near the umbilicus (belly button).
Periumbilical
A history of obesity, which can be defined as a body mass index of 30 or greater, in the mother of a fetus or index patient.
Maternal obesity during pregnancy
A history of amniocentesis having been performed in the mother of a fetus or index patient.
Maternal amniocentesis
Description of conditions in which age of onset is highly variable even in family members who share the same disease-associated variant or variants.
Typified by highly variable age of onset
Concentration or activity of an enzyme as measured in leukocytes is above or below the limits of normal.
Abnormal leukocyte enzyme concentration or activity
Concentration or activity of beta-glucuronidase (EC 3.2.1.31) below the lower limit of normal. FECH enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including cultured fibroblasts and leukocytes.
Reduced tissue beta-glucuronidase activity
Concentration or activity of an alpha-L-fucosidase as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte alpha-L-fucosidase activity
Concentration or activity of an arylsulfatase B as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte arylsulfatase B activity
Concentration or activity of an arylsulfatase C as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte steroid sulfatase activity
Concentration or activity of the lysosomal enzyme arylsulfatase A (EC 3.1.6.8) as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte arylsulfatase A activity
Activity of the enzyme alpha-galactosidase below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased alpha-galactosidase A activity
Demonstration of parasite in stool specimen, e.g., Parasites present on wet mount of stool.e
Positive fecal parasite test
Any kind of test for an infectious agent in stool positive.
Positive stool infectious agent test
Test for giardia antigen in stool such as immune assay or DFA positive.
Positive stool giardia antigen
Demonstration of antibody directed against Entamoeba histolytica in stool.
Entamoeba histolytica antibody positive in stool
Concentration of porphyrin in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced erythrocyte free porphyrin concentration
The concentration of urocanic acid in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating urocanic acid concentration
The concentration of epinephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary epinephrine level
Concentration of epinephrine in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased CSF epinephrine concentration
Concentration of epinephrin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating epinephrine concentration
Concentration of norepinephrin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating norepinephrine concentration
The concentration of norepinephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary norepinephrine level
The concentration of metanephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary metaepinephrine level
Concentration of metanephrine in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased CSF metanephrine concentration
Concentration of metanephrin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating metanephrine concentration
A swelling or enlargement localized to the ovary. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Ovarian mass
A swelling or enlargement localized to the adrenal gland. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Adrenal mass
A swelling or enlargement localized to the uterus. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Uterine mass
Calcium deposits in the prostate gland.
Prostatic calculus
A reduction in the velocity of portal venous flow, generally measured by Doppler ultrasound. Portal venous flow is normally towards the liver with peak systolic velocities in the range of 20-40 cm/s.
Decreased portal vein velocity

A swelling or enlargement localized to the cervis of the uterus. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Uterine cervix mass
The concentration of uromodulin (also known as Tamm Horsfall protein) in the urine, normalized for usine concentration, is outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal urinary uromodulin level
The concentration of uromodulin (also known as Tamm Horsfall protein) in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary uromodulin level
The concentration of phenylacetylglutamine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urine phenylacetylglutamine level
The concentration of guanidinoacetic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urine guanidinoacetic acid level
Detection of DNA and RNA originating from an infectious agent (bacteria, viruses, parasites and fungi) in the urine.
Positive urine infectious agent nucleic acid test
Detection of Cytomegalovirus (CMV) nucleic acid in the urine by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive CMV urine nucleic acid test
Detection of Neisseria gonorrhoeae nucleic acid in the urine by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive Neisseria gonorrhoeae urine nucleic acid test
Detection of enterovirus nucleic acid in the urine by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive enterovirus urine nucleic acid test
An increase in the level of glycine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Elevated brain glycine level by MRS
An increase in the level of polyol compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Elevated brain polyol compounds by MRS
An increase in the level of gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Elevated brain gamma-aminobutyric acid by MRS
Medical history of ingestion of anticoagulants prior to presentation.
History of recent anticoagulant ingestion
Concentration of antidiuretic hormone, also known as vasopressin, is below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating antidiuretic hormone concentration
Concentration of growth hormone-releasing hormone above the upper limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating growth hormone-releasing hormone concentration
Any deviation of the concentration of a protein in the amniotic fluid from normal limits
Abnormal amniotic fluid protein concentration
Concentration of alpha-fetoprotein in the amniotic fluid below lower limit of normal.
Decreased amniotic fluid alpha-fetoprotein concentration
Concentration of vitamin E in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Increased circulating vitamin E concentration
Concentration of calcitonin, a 32-amino acid polypeptide hormone that is produced primarily by the parafollicular cells of the thyroid, in the blood circulation outside of normal limits.
Abnormal circulating calcitonin concentration
Concentration of calcitonin, a 32-amino acid polypeptide hormone that is produced primarily by the parafollicular cells of the thyroid, in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating calcitonin concentration
Concentration of thyrotropin releasing hormone below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating thyrotropin releasing hormone concentration
Concentration of uroporphyrin in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating uroporphyrin concentration
Concentration of pentacarboxylporphyrin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urine pentacarboxylporphyrin level
Concentration of hexacarboxylporphyrin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urine hexacarboxylporphyrin level
Concentration of dehydroepiandrosterone in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Increased circulating dehydroepiandrosterone concentration
Concentration of coproporphyrin in erythrocytes above the upper limit of normal.
Increased erythrocyte coproporphyrin concentration
Concentration of uroproporphyrin in erythrocytes above the upper limit of normal.
Increased erythrocyte uroproporphyrin concentration
Concentration of apolipoprotein E below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating apolipoprotein E concentration
Concentration of apolipoprotein E above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating apolipoprotein E concentration
Reduction in the size of the acrosome of the head of spermatozoa.
Acrosomal hypoplasia
Oocyte maturation arrest (OMA) can manifest as failed in vitro fetilization/intracytoplasmic sperm injection (IVF/ICSI) attempts using affected oocytes.
Oocyte maturation arrest
A structural anomaly of the anus.
Abnormal anus morphology
A functional anomaly of the anus.
Abnormal anus physiology
Reduced muscle tone of the sphincter of the anus.
Weak anal sphincter tone
Diminished activity of the enzyme 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase in muscle tissue.
Reduced muscle 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase activity
Diminished activity of the enzyme 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase in liver tissue.
Reduced liver 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase activity
Inflammation of blood vessels in the mucosa of the nasal cavity.
Nasal mucosa vasculitis
Pituitary blastoma is a distinctive anterior hypophyseal tumor of infants
Pituitary blastoma
Axonal spheroids are bubble-like biological features that form on most degenerating axons.
Peripheral axon spheroid formation
Activity of the enzyme carboxylesterase 1 in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced liver carboxylesterase 1 activity
A structural anomaly of the dermis, the layer of skin that lies beneath the epidermis and above the subcutaneous layer.
Abnormal dermis morphology
Deposition of a largely amorphous hyaline (transparent and homogeneous) substance around blood vessels in the dermis layer of the skin.
Perivascular dermis hyaline deposition
Deposition of a largely amorphous hyaline (transparent and homogeneous) substance around blood vessels in the wall of the small intestine.
Perivascular small intestinal hyaline deposition

Abnormally large keratohyalin granules (KHG). KHG are typically present in the stratum granulosum of the epidermal layer of the skin (and epithelium of the mucosae). KHG are protein structures found in the keratinocytes of the stratum granulosum.
Large keratohyaline granules
Reduced amount of lipoic acid in muscle tissue.
Decreased muscle lipoic acid content
Activity of cystathionine gamma-lyase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic cystathionine gamma-lyase activity
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the digestive system.
Digestive system neoplasm
Arthrosis, i.e., of degenerative joint disease, affecting the lumbar vertebral column.
Lumbar spondylosis
Activity of the enzyme acid maltase (also known as alpha-1,4-glucosidase) below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating acid maltase activity
Concentration of 7-dehydrocholesterol in the blood circulation outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal circulating 7-dehydrocholesterol concentration
Concentration of 7-dehydrocholesterol in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating 7-dehydrocholesterol concentration
Concentration of lathosterol in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating lathosterol concentration
Concentration of desmosterol in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating desmosterol concentration
Concentration of sialic acid in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating sialic acid concentration
The synovial fluid (also known as synovia, i.e., the fluid found in the cavities of synovial joints) contains increased quantities of white blood cells.
Purulent synovial fluid
The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells that demonstrate immunoreactivity for calsequestrin 1.
Muscle fiber calsequestrin 1-containing inclusion bodies

A myxoma (A benign tumor composed of myxomatous tissue composed of loosely-arranged spindle, polygonal, and stellate cells) localized to the palate. Clinically, such tumors may present as a sessile nodule on the hard palate.
Palatine myxoma
A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) localized in the vagina.
Vaginal myxoma
Abnormally reduced amount of collagen fibers in the dermis.
Decreased dermal collagen
Abnormal shape of keratohyaline granules in dermal keratinocytes.
Irregularly shaped keratohyaline granules

Tubular shadows are characterized by a complete absence of cells in the testicular tubules, meaning that germ cells as well as somatic Sertoli cells are absent. The cells have been replaced by hyalinization.
Tubular shadows
Presence of many apocrine hidrocystoma (cysts) on the margins of the eyelids.
Multiple eyelid margin cysts

The fibrous sheath is a structure in the midpiece of the sperm flagellum surrounding the outer dense fibers. It comprises two longitudinal columns and transverse ribs. In case of altered location of the longitudinal column in the fibrous sheath the symmetrical structure is lost, most commonly with the columns not being opposite to each other, which can be visualized by electron microscopy.
Altered location of the longitudinal column in the fibrous sheath
A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) localized to the uterus.
Uterine myxoma
A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) localized to the the cervix of the uterus.
Uterine cervix myxoma
Penetrance describes the proportion of genotype positive individuals that develop disease given a lifespan of 80 years. For example, penetrance of Neurofibromatosis type 1 is close to 100%.
Typified by complete penetrance

A rare benign chondroid and osteoid matrix-producing neoplasm of bone characterized by extensive myxoid changes. OMX originate from bony cortices and have been observed in the nasal region, as well as the tibia and radius.
Osteochondromyxoma
A low-grade central nervous system tumor composed of dysplastic ganglion cells, usually presenting in children or young adults and located in the cerebral hemispheres.
Gangliocytoma
A gastrinoma, a neuroendocrine tumors characterized by the secretion of gastrin with resultant excessive gastric acid production, that is localized to the duodenum.
Duodenal gastrinoma
A primary thymic neuroendocrine tumor.
Thymic carcinoid tumor
Count of eosinophils in the bone marrow above the upper limit of normal.
Bone marrow eosinophilia
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by treatment with lithium.
Exacerbated by lithium exposure
Activity of glycogen debrancher enzyme (also known as amylo-1,6-glucosydase, 4-alpha-glucantransferase) in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic glycogen debrancher enzyme activity

Insertion of the neck and midpiece into the head of a spermatozoon on an axis that diverges from the midline axis of the spermatozoon head. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this defect is above the upper limit of normal.
Asymmetrical insertion of the midpiece into the head
Sharply angled insertion of the neck and midpiece into the head of a spermatozoon. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this feature is above the upper limit of normal.
Bent sperm neck
The concentration of 3,6-epoxydicarboxylic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 3,6-epoxydicarboxylic acid level

Presence of biliary sludge (a mixture of particulate solids that have precipitated from bile) in the gallbladder. Such sediment consists of cholesterol crystals, calcium bilirubinate pigment, and other calcium salts. Sludge is usually detected on transabdominal ultrasonography.
Gallbladder biliary sludging
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by treatment with amiodarone.
Exacerbated by amiodarone exposure
A swelling or enlargement localized to the ureter. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Ureteral mass
Width of the cavum septum pellucidum above the upper limit of normal, which is defined as a separation of greater than one cm of the leaves of the cavum septum pellucidum.
Wide cavum septum pellucidum
Underdevelopment of the trochlear nerve, which is the fourth cranial nerve and one of the ocular motor nerves that controls eye movement.
Hypoplastic trochlear nerve
A closed sac of tissue (cyst) located in the thymus. Thymic cysts are a rare, benign anomaly, are usually asymptomatic, and mostly occur in the anterior mediastinum .
Thymic cyst
A closed sack of tissue (cyst) located in the uterus.
Uterine cyst
A swelling or enlargement localized to the urinary bladder. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Urinary bladder mass
A series of indentations or erosions on a normally smooth margin of the inner layer of the cortex (i.e. the endosteum) of bones.
Endosteal scalloping
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the urinary bladder.
Urinary bladder hamartoma
A swelling or enlargement localized to the peritoneal cavity. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Peritoneal mass
A swelling or enlargement localized to the Fallopian tube. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Fallopian tube mass
Congenital absence of the pyramids, that is, of the paired structures located at the medial aspect of the ventral medulla that flank the anterior median fissure.
Aplasia of the pyramids of the medulla oblongata
A deformity of the posterior skull with bulging of the midportion of the occipital bone that is often associated with a benign variant of the mendosal suture.
Bathrocephaly
Downward pointing exostoses of the occipital bone situated in the tendinous insertions of the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles.
Occipital horn

A developmental defect characterized by failure to develop of the pituitary stalk. The pituitary stalk, also known as the infundibulum or infundibular stalk, is the connection between the hypothalamus and the pituitary gland.
Absent pituitary stalk
A structural anomaly of the pituitary stalk, also known as the infundibulum or infundibular stalk, is the connection between the hypothalamus and the pituitary gland.
Abnormal pituitary stalk morphology

A developmental defect characterized by a discontinuity of the pituitary stalk. The pituitary stalk, also known as the infundibulum or infundibular stalk, is the connection between the hypothalamus and the pituitary gland.
Interrupted pituitary stalk
Unintentional movement in one area of the face produced during intentional movement of another area of the face.
Facial synkinesis
Unintentional movement in one area of the body produced during intentional movement of another area of the body.
Synkinesis
History of exposure to birds.
Exposure to birds
Loss of sensation to the area of buttocks, perianal space and thighs.
Perianal anesthesia

Instillation of 2.5% phenylephrine drops into the eye does not induce blanching of eye redness. Failure to blanch suggests redness caused by scleral vessel engorgement (e.g., scleritis) or extravascular cause (e.g., hemorrhage), not episcleritis or conjunctivitis.
Failure of phenylephrine to induce blanching of eye redness
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to ethanol (alcohol).
Fetal alcohol exposure
Diminished ability of cells to transport cobalamine from the extracellular space to the cytoplasm.
Reduced cellular cobalamin uptake
A localized area of cell death, often accompanied by infiltration of inflammatory cells, in the brainstem.
Focal necrotic brainstem lesion
A localized area of cell death, often accompanied by infiltration of inflammatory cells, in the optic nerve.
Focal necrotic optic nerve lesion
A localized area of cell death, often accompanied by infiltration of inflammatory cells, in the thalamus.
Focal necrotic thalamus lesion
Accumulation of fluid in the interstitial spaces of the skin. This finding can be appreciated my microscopic examination of a skin biopsy.
Interstitial dermal edema
Shoulder abduction contracture

A type of shoulder contracture characterized by decreased internal rotation of shoulder, that is, by a chronic reduction in active and passive ability to internally rotate the humerus at the shoulder joint (if the arm is flexed at the elbow, Internal rotation of the shoulder rotates the forearm towards the center of the body).
Shoulder external rotation contracture

A type of thumb contracture characterized by a chronic reduction in active and passive ability of the metacarpal-phalangeal and/or interphalangeal joints of the thumb to bring from medial side to neutral position, where the neutral position for the thumb is when the distal and proximal segments of the thumb joint are in linear alignment.
Thumb adduction contracture
Hip internal rotation contracture
Activity of fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (EC 3.1.3.11) below the lower limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including liver and leukocytes.
Reduced tissue fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase activity
Activity of carbamoylphosphate synthetase 1 in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic carbamoylphosphate synthetase 1 activity
Reduced number of small nerve fibers in the skin.
Reduced intraepidermal small nerve fiber density
A developmental defect characterized by the presence of a supernumerary femoral artery.
Femoral artery duplication

Collagen VII is the major molecular constituent of anchoring fibrils in the skin. Collagen VII is synthesized as three identical pro-alpha1(VII) polypeptide chains, which are hydroxylated and glycosylated in a coordinated manner and then fold into triple-helical procollagen VII in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER). Mature collagen VII undergoes a multistep fibril polymerization process to form the anchoring fibrils. Mutant pro-alpha1(VII) polypeptide chains or procollagen VII molecules do not pass the ER quality control and are retained in the ER or designated for ubiquitin-proteasome degradation resulting in reduced amounts of collagen VII in the skin.
Intracellular accumulation of collagen VII
Diminished amount of the anchoring fibrils in the basement membrane zone that normally attach the epithelium to the basement membrane.
Reduced reticular lamina anchoring fibril density
Diminished amount of the anchoring filaments that normally bridge the lamina lucida and insert into the lamina densa in the cutaneous basement membrane zone.
Reduced lamina lucida anchoring filament density
Amount of keratin 5 in the epidermis below the lower limit of normal. The findiong is typically ascertained by immunofluorescent microscopy.
Reduced epidermal keratin 5 protein expression
Amount of keratin 14 in the epidermis below the lower limit of normal. The findiong is typically ascertained by immunofluorescent microscopy.
Reduced epidermal keratin 14 protein expression
Amount of one or more keratins in the epidermis below the lower limit of normal. The findiong is typically ascertained by immunofluorescent microscopy.
Reduced epidermal keratin protein expression
Activity of alanine-glyoxylate aminotransferase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic alanine-glyoxylate aminotransferase activity
Presence of an increased amount of blood in the hepatic capillaries.
Hepatic sinusoidal dilatation

The cross-sectional size (diameter) of the midpiece of the spermatozoon is below the lower limit of normal. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this defect is above the upper limit of normal.
Thin spermatozoon midpiece

Increased width of the midpiece of the spermatozoon. The midpiece is the structure that is located between the head and the flagella (tail) of the spermatozoon. This term applies if the width of the midpiece increases progressively from the flagella to the head and if the proportion of individual spermatozoa with this anomaly is above the upper limit of normal.
Thick spermatozoon midpiece insertion

A type of shoulder contracture characterized by a chronic reduction in the active and passive ability to abduct the shoulder. This results in the shoulders being closer to midline. The affected individual is not able to position the shoulders away from the body.
Shoulder adduction contracture
Exposure to a substance that results from the performance of an employee's duties.
Occupational exposure history
A history of exposure to silver that has occurred in relation to performance of job duties.
Occupational silver exposure
Any structural abnormality of the femoral artey, a large blood vessel that provides oxygenated blood to lower extremity structures and in part to the lower anterior abdominal wall.
Abnormal femoral artery morphology
Abnormal extrahepatic bile duct morphology
Accumulation of fibrous connective tissue (collagen) in the extrahepatic bile ducts.
Extrahepatic bile duct fibrosis

Concentration of short-chain acylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. Acylcarnitines are classified according to the number of carbon atoms in the acyl-chain. Short chain acylcarnitines have between two and five carbon atoms in the acyl-chain (C2-C5),
Elevated circulating short-chain acylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of C4 acylcarnitines in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. C4 acylcarnitines have a four-carbon acyl chain.
Elevated circulating C4 acylcarnitine concentration

Concentration of medium-chain acylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. Acylcarnitines are classified according to the number of carbon atoms in the acyl-chain. Medium-chain acylcarnitines have between six and twelve carbon atoms in the acyl-chain (C6-C12),
Elevated circulating medium-chain acylcarnitine concentration

Concentration of long-chain acylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. Acylcarnitines are classified according to the number of carbon atoms in the acyl-chain. Long-chain acylcarnitines have between thirteen and twenty carbon atoms in the acyl-chain (C13-C20),
Elevated circulating long-chain acylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of C5 acylcarnitines in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. C5 acylcarnitines have a five-carbon acyl chain.
Elevated circulating C5 acylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of C18 acylcarnitines in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. C18 acylcarnitines have a eighteen-carbon acyl chain.
Elevated circulating C18 acylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of C16 acylcarnitines in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. C16 acylcarnitines have a sixteen-carbon acyl chain.
Elevated circulating C16 acylcarnitine concentration

Concentration of very long-chain acylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. Acylcarnitines are classified according to the number of carbon atoms in the acyl-chain. Very long-chain acylcarnitines have twentyone or more carbon atoms in the acyl-chain (C21 and higher),
Elevated circulating very long-chain acylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of acetylcarnitine (C2 acylcarnitine) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. Acetylcarnitine has a two-carbon acyl chain.
Elevated circulating acetylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of methylmalonylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating methylmalonylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of 3-hydroxyhexadecanoylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating 3-hydroxyhexadecanoylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of C6 acylcarnitines in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. C6 acylcarnitines have a six-carbon acyl chain.
Elevated circulating C6 acylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of methylglutarylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating methylglutarylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of 3-hydroxyisovalerylcarnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating 3-hydroxyisovalerylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of 3-hydroxyhexanoylcarnitine (C6-OH) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating 3-hydroxyhexanoylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of carnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating carnitine concentration
Concentration of tiglylcarnitine (C5:1) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating tiglylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of acetylcarnitine (C2 acylcarnitine) in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal. Acetylcarnitine has a two-carbon acyl chain.
Reduced circulating acetylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of octadecenoylcarnitine (C18:1 acylcarnitine) in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating octadecenoylcarnitine concentration
The amount of adipose tissue (fat) in the body or a part of the body is below the lower limit of normal.
The concentration of iron in the blood circulation is outside the limits of normal.
Recurrent abnormal consumption of food, liquids, or objects that could have negative consequences for the individual.
The concentration of iron in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Applies to a sign or symptom that is distributed around the nipples or located in the nipples.
Nipple localization
The term breast microcalcification is used to define calcium deposits in the breast with a diameter of less than 1 mm.
Breast microcalcification
Architectural distortion is defined as an architectural disruption of the normal breast that does not have obvious mass opacities, which may be early signs of breast carcinoma.
Architectural distortion of breast
Thickening of the skin around the nipple with a distribution that is not equal on all sides.
Asymmetric thickening of the nipple-areolar complex

Perimenopause, or the menopausal transition, encompasses that period of time during which physiologic changes mark progression toward a woman's final menstrual period. This phase begins with the onset of menstrual irregularities and continues until a woman reaches menopause, or one year after amenorrhea has occurred. Perimenopause can last for a variable amount of time, the median of which is four years.
Perimenopausal
Mastitis is defined as an inflammation of the breast and may or may not be accompanied by infection.
Mastitis
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by menopause.
Ameliorated by menopause
Yielding to alternate pressure by palpating fingers so as to suggest that the area being felt contains fluid.
Fluctuance on palpation
A medical history of having undergone a vasectomy prior to the current presentation.
History of vasectomy
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the penis.
Pain in penis
A blood clot (thrombus) localized in the left ventricle. Left ventricular thrombus is a serious complication of acute myocardial infarction and also of non-ischemic cardiomyopathies.
Left ventricular thrombus
Atrophic vaginal mucosa
A type of ascites characterized by copious amounts of mucinous ascites and mucinous peritoneal implants, leading to progressive obliteration of the peritoneal cavity and intestinal obstruction.
Gelatinous ascites
Breast tissue with a lumpy or ropelike texture.
Diffuse breast nodularity
The amount of a nitrogen compound in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is outside of normal limits.
Abnormal urinary nitrogen compound level
The amount of biopterin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary biopterin level
The concentration of guanidinoacetic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is outside normal limits.
Abnormal urine guanidinoacetic acid level
The concentration of guanidinoacetic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine guanidinoacetic acid level
The amount of neopterin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary neopterin level
The amount of inosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal urinary inosine level
The amount of inosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary inosine level
The amount of guanosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal urinary guanosine level
The amount of guanosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary guanosine level
The concentration of hypoxanthine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is outside of normal limits.
Abnormal urinary hypoxanthine level
The concentration of hypoxanthine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary hypoxanthine level
An avulsion fracture (i.e., a type of fracture in which a piece of bone tears away from the site where the muscle attaches to the bone) of a bone of the pelvis.
Pelvic avulsion fracture
A break in one or more bones of the pelvis.
Pelvis fracture
Abnormal morphology of a specific peripheral nerve
Concentration of alpha-fetoprotein in the blood circulation outside normal limits.

An abnormal increase (delay) in the somatosensory central conduction time (CCT), which can be measured from the peak of N13 to the peak of N20 (peak CCT) or from the onset of N11 to the onset of N20 (onset CCT).

Subsarcolemmal, eosinophilic glass-like regions in the cytoplasm of muscle fibers. Hyaline bodies show significant reactivity to myofibrillar ATPase after acid pre-incubation and with immunohistochemistry, show intense reactivity with only slow myosin heavy chain. Electron microscopy of the affected areas show a lack of myofibrils and a uniform, finely granular matrix, sometimes suggesting a filamentous nature, containing few scattered nuclei and mitochondria.
The concentration of vitamin B12 in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Concentration of vitamin E in the blood circulation outside of normal limits.
Pressing forward of the tongue in the mouth, a retained motoric habit from infantile swallowing patterns
Excessive sleepiness or feeling of sleepiness, or difficulty staying awake despite having had adequate sleep, which persists over several days.

A solitary, bluish, smooth surfaced macule, papule or plaque that is generally round or oval in shape. The histopathology of blue nevi varies by subtype, but general characteristics include a vertical wedge or bulbous shaped proliferation of spindle cells, dendritic melanocytes, and melanophages into a sclerotic dermis or subcutis.
Atypically high degree of awkwardness or apprehension experienced when approaching or being approached by others.
A type of vasculitis (inflammation of blood vessel walls) that affects skeletal muscle tissue.
Any kind of test for an infectious agent in a specimen positive.
Positive infectious agent test
The presence of viral DNA (e.g., cytomegalovirus, herpes simplex virus, or varicella zoster virus) in the aqueous humor of the eye.
Aqueous humor viral DNA positivity
History of use of electronic cigarettes (vaping).
Electronic cigarette exposure history
Erythematous macules or patches over extensor surfaces of elbows, knuckles, knees, and ankles.
Gottron sign

Resistant hypertension is defined as above-goal elevated blood pressure in a patient despite the concurrent use of 3 antihypertensive drug classes, commonly including a long-acting calcium channel blocker, a blocker of the renin-angiotensin system (angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker), and a diuretic.
Hypertension resistant to conventional therapy

Deposition of excess calcium in the interosseous membrane of the leg, which extends between the interosseous crests of the tibia and fibula and separates the anterior and posterior muscles of the lower leg.
Tibiofibular interosseous membrane calcification
A type of elbow fracture that involves the distal humerus just above the elbow.
Supracondylar elbow fracture
Alcohol abuse or dependence.
Abnormal alcohol consumption
Thoracic lordosis refers to an abnormal curvature of the thoracic spine in which the thoracic spine displays lordosis (inward curve) instead of the normal kyphosis (outward curve).
Thoracic lordosis
Refers to pain or discomfort that is perceived to travel from the chest into the left arm.
Radiation into left arm
Refers to pain or discomfort that is perceived to travel from the chest into the right arm.
Radiation into right arm

The capability that a small joint (or a group of joints) has to move, passively and/or actively, beyond normal limits along physiological axes. Small joints include metacarpophalangeal joints, proximal interphalangeal joints, 
second to fifth metatarsophalangeal joints, and wrists.
Small joint hypermobilty

The capability that a large joint (or a group of joints) has to move, passively and/or actively, beyond normal limits along physiological axes. Large joints include shoulders, elbows, hips, knees, and ankles.
Large joint hypermobilty

Intracranial calcifications refer to calcifications within the brain parenchyma or vasculature. The five major components of the brain comprise the cerebrum, cerebellum, brain stem, pituitary gland, and hypothalamus.
Intracranial calcification
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against one or more components on the thyroid.
Anti-thyroid antibody positivity
Positive serology for a exposure to an infectious agent (i.e., examining serum for the presence of pathogen-specific antibodies).
Bloodstream pathogen-specific antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus type 2 (SARS-CoV-2).
Anti-SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the West Nile virus.
Anti-West Nile virus antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a microfilaria (parasite).
Anti-microfilaria antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of trypanosoma cruzi.
Anti-trypanosoma cruzi antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of chikungunya virus.
Anti-chikungunya virus antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of chlamydia psittaci.
Anti-chlamydia psittaci antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of herpes simplex.
Anti-herpes simplex antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a virus.
Bloodstream virus-specific antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a parasite.
Bloodstream parasite-specific antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a bacterium.
Bloodstream antibacterial antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the Japanese encephalitis virus.
Anti-Japanese encephalitis virus-specific antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of chlamydia trachomatis.
Anti-chlamydia trachomatis-specific antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the Epstein Barr virus (EBV).
Anti-Epstein-Barr virus-specific antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a parasite of the genus Babesia (parasite).
Anti-babesia-specific antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the Zika virus.
Anti-Zikavirus-specific antibody positivity
Positive (abnormal) result of a test such as polymerase chain reaction that is targeted against a nucleic acid sequence specific for a pathogen.
Positive bloodstream nucleic acid pathogen test
Detection of nucleic acid of a microfilarial parasite in the blood circulation.
Positive microfilaria PCR test in the blood circulation
Detection of nucleic acid of the JC-virus (JC-Polyomavirus, John Cunningham virus) in the blood circulation.
Positive JC-virus PCR test in the blood circulation
Implantation of the placenta over or near the internal os of the cervix.
Placenta previa
Any deviation of the concentration of an orrganic compound from the normal range. An organic compound is defined as any compound that contains a carbon atom.
Abnormal circulating organic compound concentration
Any deviation of the concentration of beta-carotene in the blood circulation from the normal range.
Abnormal circulating beta-carotene concentration
The concentration of beta-carotene in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating beta-carotene concentration
The concentration of beta-carotene in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased circulating beta-carotene concentration

Blocked mammary ducts represent an area of localized milk stasis, typically associated with breast engorgement and resulting in a localized tender breast lump or area of blushed color; the breast may feel hot; and there may be a white, painful bleb on the end of the nipple.
Mammary blocked duct
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a fungus.
Bloodstream antifungal antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a fungus of the Coccidioides genus.
Anti-coccidioidal antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a fungus of the Cryptoccous genus.
Anti-cryptococcal antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a mycoplasmal component.
Anti-mycoplasma antibody positivity

The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a rickettsial bacterium. Rickettsiae are gram-negative bacteria with an obligate intracellular life cycle circulating between mammalian hosts and hematophagous arthropod vectors
Anti-rickettsial antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Bartonella.
Anti-Bartonella henselae antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Dengue virus.
Anti-Dengue virus antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of an Arbovirus.
Anti-arbovirus antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of lymphocytic choriomeningitis virus (LCMV).
Anti-lymphocytic choriomeningitis antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of Varicella-zoster virus.
Anti-varicella-zoster antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of rubella virus.
Anti-rubella antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of cytomegalovirus (CMV).
Anti-cytomegalovirus antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of measles virus.
Anti-measles antibody positivity

The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a parasite of the genus Schistosomiasis is a parasitic disease historically known as bilharzia caused by the trematode of the genus Schistosoma. Schistosomiasis is a parasitic disease historically known as bilharzia caused by the trematode of the genus Schistosoma.
Anti-schistosoma antibody positivity

The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of a Powassan virus (POW), which is an arbovirus within the family of Flaviviruses primarily found in the Northeastern United States, Canada, and Russia. It is a zoonotic infection transmitted to humans by several tick species and is the only member of the tick-borne flaviviruses endemic to North America.
Anti-Powassan virus antibody positivity

Detection of a marker such as a protein by immunohistochemistry or related investigation techniques. The presence or absence of such markers can be used to identify cell types on the basis of a profile of expressed markers. These terms do not imply abnormality and can be used for any cell type or organ.
Marker expression
Detection of the presence of BCL2 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-BCL2 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
BCL2 expression
Detection of the presence of BCL6 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-BCL6 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
BCL6 expression
Detection of the presence of CD5 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD5 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD5 expression
Detection of the presence of CD10 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD10 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD10 expression
Detection of the presence of CD23 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD23 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD23 expression
Detection of the presence of CD38 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD38 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD38 expression
Detection of the presence of CD45 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD45 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD45 expression
Detection of the presence of cyclin D1 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-cyclin D1 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
Cyclin D1 expression
Detection of the presence of FMC7 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-FMC7 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
FMC7 expression
Detection of the presence of CD19 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD19 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD19 expression
Detection of the presence of CD20 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD20 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD20 expression
information about the patient's previous surgical treatments that might be relevant to the presenting illness or to provide optimal clinical management.
Past surgical history

Any structural abnormality of a superficial temporal artery, originating from the external carotid artery and passing over the zygomatic process. The superficial temporal artery is located on the superficial parts of the forehead and sides of the head and face.
Abnormal superficial temporal artery morphology
Patchy inflammation of the superficial temporal artery, forming isolated foci of arteritis.
Skip lesions on temporal artery biopsy

Any anomaly of brain-evoked potentials, defined as potentials generated by exteroceptive stimuli reflect synchronized activity by neuronal and axonal groups in the central nervous system (CNS) resulting from the arrival of nerve impulses after stimulation of a peripheral nerve or its receptors. Depending on the type of stimulus, evoked potentials are categorized as visual (VEP), auditory (AEP), or somatosensory (SSEP). Motor evoked potentials (MEP) occur when the brain's motor area is stimulated. They result from the activation of a sufficient number of motor units.
Abnormal brain-evoked potentials
