A past medical history of recently having retracted the penile foreskin for a prolonged period of time. Paraphimosis commonly occurs iatrogenically, when the foreskin is retracted for cleaning, placement of a urinary catheter, a procedure such as a cystoscopy, or for penile examination. Failure to return the retracted foreskin over the glans promptly after the initial retraction can lead to paraphimosis.
Prolonged retraction of penile foreskin
Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the clavicle.
Thickened cortex of the clavicle
Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the mandible.
Thickened cortex of the mandible
Minor hypoplasia (developmental undergrowth) of the thumb, whereby all musculoskeletal and neurovascular components of the digit are present, just small in size (Blauth classification).
Thumb hypoplasia grade 1

A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby all of the osseous structures are present (may be small), and there is metacarpophalangeal joint ulnar collateral ligament instability and thenar hypoplasia.
Thumb hypoplasia grade 2

A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby there are musculotendinous and osseous deficiencies with the carpometacarpal (CMC) joint intact. Absence of active motion at the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) or interphalangeal (IP) joint.
Thumb hypoplasia grade 3A

A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby there are musculotendinous and osseous deficiencies characterized by basal metacarpal aplasia with deficient carpometacarpal (CMC) joint, and absence of metacarpophalangeal (MCP) or interphalangeal (IP) joint.
Thumb hypoplasia grade 3B
A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb characterized by attachment to the hand only by the skin and digital neurovascular structures.
Thumb hypoplasia grade 4

Multiple multiple, small, well-defined radiodense foci of cortical-like bone in the medullary space parallel to the trabeculae located in the femur. The loci correspond to condensations of the lamellar trabeculae on histology.
Femoral osteopoikilosis
Pain or tenderness in the region of the carotid artery.
Carotidynia
A substantial difference in blood pressure (e.g., 20 mmHg) between the right and left arms.
Asymmetric blood pressure between arms

A congenital anomaly that appears as an amputation at different levels of the leg, e.g. femur, foreleg, ankle or toe. The limb is missing the terminal (distal) segment(s), with preservation of all the segment(s) proximal to the missing segment.
Transverse terminal lower limb defect
A developmental defect leading to a transverse deficiency with absence of the lower leg (eg tibia and fibula), ankle and foot.
Hemimelia of lower leg
A developmental defect leading to a transverse deficiency with absence of the forearm (eg ulna and radius), wrist and hand.
Hemimelia of forearm

History of having been treateed with a sodium glucose transport inhibitors such as dapagliflozin, empagliflozin, canagliflozin, sglt-i, SGLT2, bexagliflozin, ertugliflozin, sotagliflozin, jardiance, invokana, forxiga, brenzavvy, steglatro, inpefa.
Sodium glucose transport inhibitor exposure

A benign paroxysmal nonepileptic disorder occurring in healthy children 6 to 48 months of age. The episodes start with a provocation such as emotional upset or minor injury, and might progress to breath holding, cyanosis, and syncope.
Breath-holding spell
The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of the proximal tibia.
Flared proximal tibial metaphysis
Delayed maturation and calcification of any of the toe phalanges.
Delayed toe phalanx ossification
A history of ingestion of a relatively high amount of foods containing sorbitol.
Sorbitol ingestion
Growth of bacteria in a culture dervied from ascites fluid.
Positive peritoneal fluid bacterial culture

Accumulation of cystine crsytals in the eye. Patients present with crystal accumulation affecting the cornea and conjunctiva, but crystals can also be deposited in the iris, ciliary body, choroid and retinal pigment epithelium (RPE), and lens capsule. Corneal crystal deposition starts in infancy in the anterior periphery of the cornea, and progresses centrally and posteriorly. The crystals, which have a fine, uniform needle-shaped structure, are diffusely distributed within the corneal tissues.
Ocular cystine crystal deposition

A manifestation of abnormal wound healing in which there is formation of excessive granulation tissue, with the granulation tissue rising above the level of surrounding skin and creating a raised, reddish, moist, and bumpy surface.
Exuberant granulation tissue
A small (less than 5 mm in diameter), elevated, circumscribed, solid, palpable mass located in thte mucosa of the oral cavity.
Oral mucosal papule
Abnormally increased degree of goose bump formation, that is, of involuntary formation of bumps on a person's skin at the base of body hairs.
Excessive piloerection
A palpable swelling in the scalp caused by an increase in interstitial fluid volume (excess fluid).
Scalp edema
A slightly raised and often reddish serpentine or curvilinear path in the skin.
Serpiginous burrow
Detection of rabies nucleic acid in brain tissue by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive brain-tissue rabies nucleic acid test
Detection of Bordetella pertussis PCR nucleic acid in in nasopharyngeal secretions by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive respiratory tract Bordetella pertussis nucleic acid test

Demonstration of acid-fast bacilli by microscopic examination of wound tissue. Acid fastness is a physical property that gives a bacterium the ability to resist decolorization by acids during staining procedures.
Demonstration of acid-fast bacilli in wound tissue
Identification of encapsulated budding yeasts in smears of body fluids, secretions, exudates, or other specimens.
Positive tissue encapsulated budding yeast test
Growth of coccidioidomycosis in a culture derived from skin or an organ.
Positive tissue coccidioidomycosis culture
Concentration or activity of dihydropteridine reductase (EC 1.6.99.7) below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and erythrocytes.
Diminished tissue dihydropteridine reductase activity
Concentration of transcobalamin I in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating transcobalamin I concentration
Concentration of cationic trypsinogen in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Diminished circulating cationic trypsinogen concentration
The activity or concentration of hyaluronidase in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Diminished circulating hyaluronidase activity
Rate of proteoglycan sulfation (sulfotransferase activity) is below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Diminished sulfotransferase activity in cultured fibroblasts

Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.50) above the upper limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. It is also known as alpha-acetylglucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase, and alpha-D-2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucosidase.
Elevated tissue alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase activity

Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.50) outside of the limits of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. It is also known as alpha-acetylglucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase, and alpha-D-2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucosidase.
Abnormal tissue alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase activity
The concentration of trihydroxycholestanoic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating trihydroxycholestanoic acid concentration
The concentration of glyoxylic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating glyoxylic acid concentration
Concentration of sepiapterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF sepiapterin concentration
Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of stainable substances within hepatocytes.
Intrahepatic inclusion bodies
Presence of abnormal vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles) in the sarcolemma. The vacuoles are often associated with cytoplasmic and occasionally intranuclear eosinophilic inclusions.
Muscle vacuoles

Presence of abnormal vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles) in the sarcolemma. On histological staining with hematoxylin and eosin, non-rimmed vacuoles lack the prominent dark border (rim) seen in rimmed vacuoles.
Nonrimmed muscle vacuoles
Activity or concentration of glycogen phosphorylase L in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic glycogen phosphorylase activity
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages observed in the bone marrow.
Bone marrow hemophagocytosis

Splenic inflammation involving a granulomatous response, i.e., a non-specific inflammatory response involving granulomas, defined as a compact organized collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes including epithelioid and giant cells.
Splenic granulomatosis
Loss of erection at the time point of pain or other symptom onset.
Immediate detumescence of penis at time of symptom onset
History of having received a surgical replacement of the aortic valve.
History of aortic valve replacement

An ST-segment elevation of at least 2 mm in at least one right precordial lead (V1 to V3), followed by an r'-wave and a concave or straight ST segment. The descending ST segment crosses the isoelectric line and is followed by a negative and symmetric T-wave.
Coved type ST segment elevation

An ST-segment elevation of at least 0.5 mm (generally at least 2 mm in V2) in at least one right precordial lead (V1 to V3), followed by a convex ST. The r'-wave may or may not overlap the J point, but it has a slow downward slope. The ST segment is followed by a positive T-wave in V2 and is of variable morphology in V1.
Saddle-back type ST segment elevation
A blood concentration of ethanol that is consistent with alcohol intoxication, generally assumed to be 0.0800 g/dL or higher.
Substantially elevated circulating ethanol concentration
Abnormal twisting or winding of the stomach.
Tortuous appearance of the stomach
A developmental defect causing an absence of the cochlear nerve resulting in sensorineural hearing loss.
Cochlear nerve aplasia
Abnormally small lateral ventricle with a slit-like appearance.
Slit-like lateral ventricle
A history of exposure during pregnancy (including during the period of conception) of the mother of a fetus or child to methamphetamine.
Fetal methamphetamine exposure
Concentration of 4-hydroxybutyric acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating 4-hydroxybutyric acid concentration
The amount of 2,4-dihydroxybutyric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary 2,4-dihydroxybutyric acid level
A higher than normal tendency of parasympathomimetic agents to induce miosis.
Pupillary hypersensitivity to parasympathomimetic agents

4-hydroxyamphetamine is used in eye drops to dilate the pupil, e.g.., to induce mydriasis for fundus examinations. This term refers to a lack of response of the pupil to topical application of 4-hydroxyamphetamine.
Lack of pupillary response to hydroxyamphetamine
Abnormal morphology of subcortical U fibers, typically as assessed by abnromal intensity on magnetic resonance imaging of the brain.
Subcortical U fiber lesion
A lipoma (a benign encapsulated mass with lobulated mature adipose tissue enclosed by fibrous tissue) located within the spine but outside of the dura mater.
Intraspinal extradural lipoma

An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to the nasal cavity. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Intranasal mass

Subcapsular hepatic rupture is characterized by the development of a hematoma, often quite large, beneath the liver capsule. An interval of days or hours may elapse between the time of injury and the first appearance of symptoms. A history of injury may be entirely lacking, or may be so unremarkable that it is elicited only by diligent interrogation. The hematoma tends to increase in size.
Liver rupture
The amount of mandelic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary mandelic acid
The amount of malic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine malic acid level
The amount of 3-hydroxysebacic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 3-hydroxysebacic acid level
The amount of vanillactic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary vanillactic acid level
The amount of 4,5-dihydroxyhexanoic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 4,5-dihydroxyhexanoic acid level
The amount of hydroxyphenyllactic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine hydroxyphenyllactic acid level
Demonstration of the presence of cytomegalovirus in the stomach by means of a method such as in-situ hybridization.
Positive gastric CMV intranuclear inclusions
The amount of dihydroxycholestanoic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine dihydroxycholestanoic acid level
The amount of bile alcohol in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary bile alcohol level
The amount of glucose tetrasaccharide in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine glucose tetrasaccharide level
The amount of 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urine 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate level
Lack of ability to purse or pucker the lips.
Inability to protrude lips

Wet voice is a perceptual vocal quality that is gurgly or liquid sounding and is due to the voice being produced through moisture. It is commonly used as an indicator of penetration and/or aspiration in clinical swallowing assessments and bedside screening tests.
Wet voice

An erythematous (pink-red, depending on the skin color of the affected individual) macule that spreads peripherally and coalesces to form polycyclic or serpentine patches or plaques. Lesions occur in crops over days to weeks and are evanescent. The rate of migration is 2 to 12 mm over a period of a few hours. Erythema marginatum tends to affect the trunk more than the extremities and to not be accompanied by pruritus.
Erythema marginatum

Mechanic's hands are fissured, erythematous, hyperkeratotic eruptions on the hands, resembling the type of occupational dermatosis said to resemble the hands of a manual laborer. The lesions are classically on the lateral edges of the fingers and thumbs, largely sparing the palmar, and dorsal aspects of the digits.
Mechanic's hands
Hyperkeratotic scaly fissured plaques on the fingers/palms or soles, generally more evident on the lateral aspect of index fingers.
Hiker's feet

The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against a human leukocyte antigen (HLA-DQ). DQ is one of several antigens involved in antibody-mediated rejection of organ transplants.
Anti-HLA-DQ antibody positivity

Erythropoietin is produced and released into the blood by the kidneys in response to hypoxemia, and would normally be expected to increase with decreasing hemoglobin levels. This term applies if the increase fails to occur, as may be seen in conditions including chronic kidney disease.
Inappropriate normal or low erythropoietin
A condition in which food moves through the stomach into the small intestine at an abnormally fast rate.
Rapid gastric emptying
Abnormal deposition of calcium in mediastinal lymph nodes.
Mediastinal lymph node calcification
Eggshell calcification refers to fine calcification seen at the periphery of a mass and usually relates to lamellar lymph node calcification.
Eggshell calcification of lymph nodes
Abnormal accumulation of fluid within the knee joint or around the knee. Symptoms maye include, pain, swelling, and stiffness.
Knee joint effusion

Skin emphysema/Subcutaneous emphysema occurs when gas or air accumulates and seeps under the skin, where normally no gas should be present. While the presence of air in subcutaneous or mediastinal tissue is not dangerous in itself, prompt recognition of the underlying cause is essential.
Subcutaneous emphysema
Bone scintigraph is performed with technetium 99m-labeled diphosphonates. The uptake of these radiopharmaceuticals depicts osteoblastic activity and regional blood flow to bone.
Elevated bone scintigraphy uptake
Concentration or activity of long-chain-enoyl-CoA hydratase (EC 4.2.1.74) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.
Diminished long-chain-enoyl-CoA hydratase activity in cultured fibroblasts

Concentration or activity of acetyl-CoA C-acyltransferase (EC 2.3.1.16) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal. This enzyme catalyzes the reaction acetyl-CoA + an acyl-CoA = a 3-oxoacyl-CoA + CoA. It is also known as 3-ketoacyl-CoA thiolase and beta-ketothiolase.
Diminished acetyl-CoA C-acyltransferase activity in cultured fibroblasts

Pathological inclusion bodies are are composed of glycogen, proteins, nucleic acids, lipids, hemosiderin, and calcium, that accumulate as metabolic by-products, catabolic products of macromolecular complexes, or in the context of cell injury.
Pathological inclusion body
Diminished or absent collagen alpha5(IV) chain staining pattern in the epidermal basement membrane.
Reduced epidermal collagen IV alpha 5 chain staining
Abnormal reduction in the amount of the alpha 3 chain of collagen IV in the basement membrane of the glomeruli of the kidney.
Diminished glomerular basement membrane collagen IV alpha 3 chain staining
Abnormal reduction in the amount of the alpha 4 chain of collagen IV in the basement membrane of the glomeruli of the kidney.
Diminished glomerular basement membrane collagen IV alpha 4 chain staining
Abnormal reduction in the amount of the alpha 5 chain of collagen IV in the basement membrane of the glomeruli of the kidney.
Diminished glomerular basement membrane collagen IV alpha 5 chain staining
Deposition of cystine crystals in kidney tissue. Cystine crystals display a pathognomic hexagonal shape.
Cystine nephrolithiasis
Accumulation of cystine in the liver.
Hepatic cystine accumulation
The presence of cystine crystals in bone marrow cells as demonstrated in a fresh bone marrow aspiration sample.
Bone marrow cystine accumulation

Desmoid tumors are rare, locally aggressive, fibroblastic soft-tissue tumors that are characterized by infiltrative growth and tendency to recur. Desmoid tumors do not metastasize but can arise in any part of the body: extra-abdominal (appear in the head and neck, chest, extremities), and abdominal wall or intra-abdominal (originating in tissue that connects abdominal organs).
Desmoid tumor
A segment of the jejunum that runs parallel to the normal jejunum and communicates with the jejunal lumen at one or both ends.
Tubular jejunal duplication
A full thickness tear or breakage of the myocardium of the left ventricle.
Left ventricular rupture
Multiple punctate (speckled, patchy spot-like) and/or curvilinear areas of gadolinium enhancement distributed around blood vessels in the pons.
Punctate pontine perivascular enhancement

Presence of one or more adult worms in the intestine as demonstrated by sonography or passage of a worm in the stool. On sonography, worms may appear as linear, echogenic structures within the intestines.
Intestinal worm
Demonstration of one or more worms in the scrotum. This finding can be appreciated by sonography, where echogenic, linear structures could be seen moving within the scrotum.
Scrotal worm
A small bowel tumor with adenomatous epithelium.
Small intestinal adenoma

Mottling (spots or blotches with different shades) of the retinal pigment epithelium in the mother of the index patient. Retinal mottling may indicate a mosaic X-linked inactivation state in the mother.
Maternal retinal mottling

A stretched conical-shaped structure found at the gallbladder neck with several linear echoes converging towards its tip. This finding is demonstrated by sonography and can indicate gallbladder volvulus.
Twisted gallbladder pedicle
Fistula between the gallbladder and the intestine.
Cholecyst-enteric fistula
Impaired ability to accurately measure or estimate time intervals.
Dyschronometria
History of recently intermittent breastfeeding an infant (i.e., on and off).
History of recent intermittent breastfeeding
A benign, fluid-filled sac in the breast.
Breast cyst
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are well-defined and localized to a specific area.
Circumscribed
Applies to an abnormality that displays multiple indentations and/or elevations producing an irregular surface contour.
Lobulated
Applies to an abnormality with irregular, radiating, or spiky edges.
Spiculated
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles series of a concentric circles or spirals.
Whorled
Delta brushes are transient patterns characterised by a slow delta wave with superimposed fast activity.
Delta brush pattern on EEG
Fusion of the junction between the distal tibia, fibula and the talus.
Tibiotalar synostosis
he term given when a vertebral body has lost almost its entire height anteriorly and posteriorly, representing a very advanced compression fracture.
Vertebra plana
An abnormal gait caused by a rotational variation anywhere in the lower extremity that causes the foot to point inward, instead of pointing straight ahead or outward, when walking or running.
Intoeing
A vibration felt upon palpation of a blood vessel over an extremity.
Palpable thrill on extremity
The feet turn excessively outward when walking, caused by a rotational variation in the leg.
Out-toeing
An abnormal separation between the talo-tibial joint.
Ankle dislocation
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against neuronal intermediate filament.
Anti-neuronal intermediate filament antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against dendritic spine scaffolding protein Drebrin.
Anti-DREBRIN antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against anti-lipoprotein lipase.
Anti-lipoprotein lipase autoantibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against apoCII.
Anti-apolipoprotein CII autoantibody positivity
The presence of intracellular inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in neurons that stain with eosin, a red or pink dye.
Eosinophilic neuronal inclusion bodies
A characteristic smell said to resemble the odor of dirty socks.
Sweaty foot-like odor
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against acetylcholine receptor.
Anti-acetylcholine receptor antibody positivity
Applies to an abnormality that is located on hair shafts.
Hair shaft lesion
History of use of tightly fitting shoes for a long period of time.
Prolonged use of tightly fitting footwear
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about ingestion of high quantities of protein.
Triggered by high protein intake
An abnormally increased thickness of a leaflet of the tricuspid valve.
Thickened tricuspid valve cusp
Abnormal shifting of the anterior fontanelle fropm its normal central position.
Displaced anterior fontanelle
Accumulation of cerebral spinal fluid in the subdural space.
Subdural hygroma

Incus ankylosis refers to congenital or acquired fixation of the incus, which is associated with conductive hearing resulting from impairment of the sound-conduction mechanism (the external auditory canal, tympanic membrane, and/or middle-ear ossicles).
Incus ankylosis
A tendency to reject a variety of foods and/or to eat a restricted range of foods.
Excessive diet restriction
Dyskinesis is used to describe ventricular muscle segments that bulge outside the left ventricular cavity during systole, as opposed to contracting inwards with the rest of the segments.
Left ventricular apical dyskinesis
A longitudinal red band extending from the proximal nail fold or lunula to the distal nail plate.
Longitudinal erythronychia
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by exposure to sunlight.
Exacerbated by exposure to sunlight
Applied to a sign or symptom that is made worse by exposure to heat (high ambient temperatures).
Exacerbated by heat
Applied to a sign or symptom that is made worse by excessive sweating.
Exacerbated by excessive sweating
The accumulation of a significant amount of exudate in the pleural space, accompanied by the presence of malignant cells or tumour tissue.
Malignant pleural effusion

In diabetes insipidus, affected individuals produce large quantities of dilute urine. In nephrogenic DI, the kidneys do not respond to vasopressin. In a water deprivation test or with administration of exogenous vasopressin, the osmolaltiy of the urine does not increase as normally.
Inappropriately low urine osmolality following challenge
Abnormally low ratio of tetrahydrocortisol (THF) plus 5-alpha-THF to tetrahydrocortisone (THE).
Reduced urine tetrahydrocortisol plus 5-alpha-THF to tetrahydrocortisone ratio
The amount of 2,4-dihydroxyglutarate in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary 2,4-dihydroxyglutarate level

An abnormal result of the xylose absorption test that is used to assess the ability of the intestines to absorb D-xylose. D-xylose is a five-carbon monosaccharide found in some plants. The patient drinks a solution containing a specific amount of D-xylose and the concentration of xylose is measured in the blood circulation and then in the urine. A low amount of D-xylose indicates reduced small intestinal absorbtion.
Abnormal urine D-xylose test
An abnormal growth or accumulation of tissue in a hemisphere of the cerebrum. Typically a mass is an initial finding that will lead to additional workup.
Cerebral hemisphere mass lesion
Increased signal on T2 magnetic resonance imaging characterized by a linear region of high signal surrounding the lateral aspect of the putamen at 1.5 Tesla.
T2-hyperintense putaminal rim
An abnormal growth or accumulation of tissue in the posterior fossa, affecting the cerebellum or fourth ventricle. Typically a mass is an initial finding that will lead to additional workup.
Posterior fossa mass lesion
Abnormal increased variability in the timing between consecutive R-waves on an electrocardiogram.
Irregular RR interval
Abnormally increased variability in the timing between consecutive P-waves on an electrocardiogram.
Irregular P-P interval
Demonstration of fungi growing on hair by a method such as microscopy of hairs mounted on slides with 10% potassium hydroxide.
Fungal hair infection
A past medical history of having long, full hair.
Long hairstyle

fine white linear scars under intact conjunctival epithelium. This scarring appears in areas of previous conjunctival ulceration or pseudomembrane formation, weeks to months after the insult is healed.
Conjunctival subepithelial fibrosis
Abnormal reduction in depth of the fornix of the conjunctiva. The fornix is the area where the conjunctiva folds back upon itself, thereby creating a recessed space.
Conjunctival fornix foreshortening
History of exposure to ultraviolet light, such as may be encountered with outdoor activities, living near equator, radiation.
Strong ultraviolet light exposure
A history of intravaginal cleansing with a liquid solution for personal hygiene or aesthetic reasons.
Exposure to vaginal douching
A history of applying oily lotions or creams to the skin.
Exposure to oily lotions or creams

Concentration of pristanic acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. This finding can be observed in Zellweger syndrome. Note that branched-chain fatty acid accumulation depends on dietary intake of phytanic acid, which is minimal in formula- and breast-fed infants. Thus, phytanic and pristanic acid levels are normal in a neonate with Zellweger spectrum disorder.
Elevated circulating pristanic acid concentration following branched-chain fatty acid ingestion
Reduction in the level of ZAP-70 protein CD4-positive T cells.
Decreased CD4+ T cell ZAP-70 protein expression
A type of contracture in which the dorsal flexion muscles of the ankle are contracted.
Dorsal flexion contracture of the ankle
Lack of the normal diaphyseal constriction (thinning of long bones toward the midshaft area) giving the submetaphyseal areas an abnormally wide appearance.
Metaphyseal undermodelling
Compression of the common iliac vein against the spine by the contralateral common iliac artery.
Iliac vein compression
Detection of abnormal amyloid deposits in the body by 123I-labeled serum amyloid P component (SAP) scintigraphy.
Positive serum amyloid P scintigraphy
Motor and/or sensory cranial nerve findings ipsilateral to the lesion, and at the same time motor and/or sensory findings on the contralateral side of the body.
crossed brainstem sign
Reduced ability to inflate the cheeks by blowing air into them while keeping the lips closed.
Inability to puff cheeks

Visual sensations caused by changes within the eye itself, rather than by the normal light stimulation process. Entoptic phenomena are classified in the syndrome as floaters, blue field entoptic phenomenon, photopsia and self-light of the eye.
Entoptic phenomenon

An abnormality of the vestibulospinal (VS) reflexes, which contribute to the control of postural orientation. In this task, they continuously collaborate with reflexes elicited by stimulation of visual and somatosensory receptors. Labyrinthine receptors are sensitive to modifications (i) of the head position with respect to the earth vertical or (ii) of the angular/linear velocity of head motion in space. This information can be used to monitor deviations from the maintained body position.
Abnormal vestibulo-spinal reflex

An abnormal result of the probe-to-bone (PTB) test. The PTB test is performed by inserting a sterile, metal surgical probe into the ulcer and is positive if a hard, gritty surface is felt inside. For large wounds, this may require gentle exploration of the wound with the probe.
Positive probe-to-bone test
A history of exposure to repetitive impact on palm or hand, such as working with a jackhammer.
Exposure to repetitive hand impact
A partial or complete breakage of the scaphoid bone.
Fractured scaphoid bone
Resistance to the effects of local anaesthesia, with delayed onset or failure of local anesthetics to incude numbness or relieve pain.
Local anesthetic ineffectiveness
Applied to lesions whose distribution is confined or restricted to the palms of the hands and soles of the feet.
Palmoplantar location
A raised, flat-topped lesion with a diameter of one centimeter or more that is located in the mucosa of the mouth.
Oral mucosa plaque
Detection of rabies nucleic acid in saliva by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive saliva rabies nucleic acid test
Activity of arylsulfatase A (EC 3.1.6.8) above the upper limit of normal. The activity can be measured in multiple tissues including culutured fibroblasts and leukocytes or in the blood circulation.
Elevated tissue arylsulfatase A activity
The concentration of a methysterol in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating methysterol concentration

The amount of adipic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. Adipic acid is an alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,4-dicarboxy derivative of butane.
Elevated urinary adipic acid
Slow-wave activity observed in the temporal area of the scalp electro-encephalogram (EEG).
EEG with temporal slowing
Medical history of the hand having come into contact with the nozzle of a high-pressure injecting system such as a paint gun or air compressor.
History of high-pressure injection injury of the hand
Excessively long styloid process of the ulna.
Hypertrophic ulnar styloid process
A history of placement of a peripehral venous catheter in the hours, days, or weeks before the current presenting complaint.
History of recent peripheral venous catheter
Exudation of a thick, opaque fluid from a wound or skin lesion, typically as a result of infection and draining pus, i.e., dead white blood cells, bacteria, and tissue debris.
Purulent drainage from skin
A history of exposure of fingers by putting them in other peoples' mouths occupationally, e.g., as a dentist or physician.
Occupational history of putting fingers in other people's mouths
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are limited to or predominantly affect a single finger.
Single-finger involvement
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance affect more than one finger.
Multiple-finger involvement
Exquisite tenderness in a specific region, beyond what one would surmise from examination.
Pain disproportionate to abnormality on physical exam

Hypoplasia or aplasia of the greater or lesser wing of the sphenoid bone, typically resulting in widening of the superior orbital fissure, elevation of the [lesser sphenoid wing, and ipsilateral orbital enlargement.
Sphenoid wing dysplasia
An injury in which skin and underlying tissues are cut or torn.
Skin laceration
A partial or complete breakage of a metacarpal bone.
Metacarpal fracture
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort localized to the base of the thumb, over thenar eminence or thumb metacarpal.
Pain at the base of the thumb
Medical history of participation in sports (football, basketball, soccer, skiing) in the hours, days, or weeks prior to the current presenting complaint.
History of recent participation in athletics
History of trauma months to years ago, including but not limited to fracture or other orthopedic injury at the symptomatic area.
Remote trauma history

An inflammatory condition of the joint that connects the far ends of the radius and the ulna, known as the distal radioulnar joint (DRUJ). DRUJ arthritis may be characterized by widening of the DRUJ interval, volar/dorsal displacement of the distal ulna, radiographic evidence of osteoarthritis at the DRUJ joint including osteophytes, subchondral cysts, subchrondal sclerosis, and joint space narrowing.
Distal radioulnar joint arthritis
Fracture of the proximal end of the radius involving the radial head.
Radial head fracture

An injury to the lateral collateral ligament (LCL) of the elbow. The LCL is a complex capsuloligamentous structure critical in stabilizing the ulnohumeral and radiocapitellar articulations. LCL injury can result in elbow instability, allowing the proximal radius and ulna to externally rotate away from the humerus as a supination stress is applied to the forearm.
Elbow lateral collateral ligament tear
An injury to the medial collateral ligament (MCL) of the elbow.
Elbow medial collateral ligament tear
Fracture of the coronoid process on the proximal ulna.
Coronoid fracture
A medical history of hving had a spinal cord injury prior to the presenting complaint.
History of spinal cord injury

Paresthesias in anterior/medial aspect of the thigh (anterior and medial cutaneous nerves of the thigh) and/or medial aspect of the lower leg and foot (saphenous distribution). May be accompanied by weakness in the quadriceps.
Femoral nerve distribution
Breakage (tear) of the triceps tendon.
Triceps tendon rupture
History of having been treateed with digoxin.
Digoxin exposure
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the upper arm.
Upper arm pain
A partial or complete breakage of the capitulum of the humerus, which is a smooth, rounded eminence on the lateral portion of the distal articular surface of the humerus.
Capitellum fracture
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the anterior (front) part of the shoulder.
Anterior shoulder pain

An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the front part of the elbow front part of the elbow, that is, on the ventral side of the arm where the arm bends.
Pain at the anterior aspect of the elbow
Lateral elbow x-ray showing lucent crescent of fat that indicates a joint effusion in the elbow .
Posterior fat pad sign of the elbow

An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the front part of the knee, that is, the side of the knee where the patella is located.
Pain at the anterior aspect of the knee

An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the back part of the knee, that is, opposite to the side of the knee where the patella is located.
Pain at the posterior aspect of the knee
Biceps tendinitis is inflammation of the tendon around the long head of the biceps muscle.
Biceps tendonitis
Ultrasonography showing increased cross sectional area (CSA) of a peripheral nerve as it travels through a potential site of compression.
Increased peripheral nerve cross sectional area
Pain in extremity that worsens with joint is passively flexed.
Pain exacerbated by passive flexion at joint

With forearm fully supinated and elbow flexed to 90 degrees, examiner hooks a finger a bit around the distal biceps tendon at the anterior aspect of the elbow. Test is positive when there is lack of appreciable cord like structure to hook around.
Positive hook test at the elbow
Manual downward pressure on the arm with the shoulders flexed forward to 90 degrees, elbows fully extended, and palm facing up recreates pain in the anterior shoulder region; named after Dr. Speed.
Positive Speed's test

A disruption of the greater and lesser arcs of the lunate bone, with the lunate having a triangular silhouette, know as the piece of pie sign. Often caused by falling on an outstretched hand, patients will have tenderness to palpation over the dorsum of the wrist and may have sensory deficits in the median nerve distribution.
Triangular lunate bone
Pain worsens with wrist ulnar or radial deviation.
Pain exacerbated by wrist deviation
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the side of the foot nearest to the little (fifth) toe.
Pain on the lateral aspect of the foot
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the inner side of knee, that is, the region of the knee that faces the other knee.
Pain at the medial aspect of the knee

An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the outer side of knee, that is, the region of the knee that faces away from the other knee.
Pain at the lateral aspect of the knee
A history of exposure to frequent squatting/kneeling and/or heavy lifting.
Occupational exposure to frequent kneeling

An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the structures around the greater trochanter (the bony prominence on the outer part of the femur).
Trochanteric pain
A noticeable lump or swelling in the arm or leg that you can feel with you fingers and this lump is beating or pulsating, similar to the feeling of a heartbeat.
Pulsatile mass in extremity
Any anomaly of the R wave of the EKG, which is the first upward deflection after the P wave. The R wave reflects early ventricular depolarisation.
Abnormal R wave
Absence of the normal increase in size of the R wave in the precordial leads when advancing from lead V1 to V6 of the electrocardiogram.
Poor R-wave progression

The R wave in leads V1-V2 is normally considerably smaller in amplitude than the S wave in the same leads. Prominent R wave in these leads implies the R wave is larger than the S-wave, which may indicate cardiovascular pathology. This term includes Tall R wave in lead V1, which is defined by a R/S ratio greater than 1.
Prominent V1-V2 R wave
An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to a finger.
Finger mass
An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to a foot.
Foot mass

A condition characterized by structural abnormalities of the retinal veins, including tortuosity, dilation, narrowing, or irregularities in branching patterns. These changes may be associated with systemic or ocular diseases such as retinal vein occlusion, diabetic retinopathy, or hypertensive retinopathy.
Abnormal retinal vein morphology

Spongiosis refers to the increased intercellular edema in the epidermis resulting in the pulling away of the keratinocytes from their surrounding desmosomes. Histologically, the spongiotic tissue reaction pattern involves the accumulation of fluid in the intercellular spaces of the epidermis, making the desmosomes junctions more easy to appreciate. Parakeratosis forms above the areas of spongiosis. The foci of spongiosis can be microscopic to grossly identifiable clinically with vesicles or bullae.
Spongiosis

A congenital finding where the adrenal gland does not form it's typical triangular, Y or V shape and is instead discoid, straight or elongated in shape. It is often found incidentally on renal ultrasound and is associated with renal agenesis and other renal congenital anomalies.
Discoid adrenal gland
A structural abnormality in the blood vessels of the optic disc, including bleeding, tortuosity, dilation, shunting, or other unusual branching patterns.
Abnormal optic disc vasculature morphology

Localization of symptoms such as numbness or paresthesias on the skin over the upper chest, specifically above the clavicle and over the lateral aspect of the neck, corresponding to the distribution of the supraclavicular nerve.
Supraclavicular nerve distribution

Difficulty rotating the lower part of the arm towards the body (tested with the elbow flexed and the elbow held next to the side of the body or shoulder 90 degrees abducted to the side) secondary to pain, weakness, or mechanical block.
Limited shoulder internal rotation
An anterior posterior (AP) shoulder radiograph shows distance between the the proximal aspect of the humeral head and inferior aspect of the acromion of less than 7 mm.
Superior displacement of the humeral head

intracompartmental pressure (ICP) over 30 mmHg. Acute compartment syndrome occurs when there is increased pressure within a closed osteofascial compartment, resulting in impaired local circulation. Acute compartment syndrome is considered a surgical emergency since, without proper treatment, it can lead to ischemia and eventually necrosis. Generally, acute compartment syndrome is considered a clinical diagnosis. However, ICP over 30 mmHg can be used as a threshold to aid in diagnosis.
Increased compartment pressure
Pain localized to the radial aspect of the elbow.
Pain at the lateral aspect of the elbow
Pain localized to the posterior aspect of the elbow.
Pain at the posterior aspect of the elbow
Pain localized to the medial aspect of the elbow.
Pain at the medial aspect of the elbow

Applies to the localization of findings corresponding to the distribution of the radial nevrve, such as (i)paresthesias on the dorsoradial aspect of the hand and wrist, including the dorsal thumb, index finger and middle finger and (ii) Weakness in elbow extension, wrist extension, finger extension, thumb extension and/or supination of the forearm.
Radial nerve distribution
An osseous connection between the superomedial border of the right scapula and C5-C6 spinous processes.
Omovertebral bone
Swelling on the chest between the neck and the shoulder, above the clavicel (collar bone).
Clavicular edema
The presence of antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that react against a component of measles virus.
Positive CSF anti-measles antibody test

Vertical lines in the posterior stroma of the cornea, aligned with Descemet membrane. These lines temporarily disappear with pressure applied to the cornea. Vogt striae are a hallmark feature of keratoconus but have also been observed in healthy eyes. Rare cases of horizontal striae have been reported.
Vogt striae

A condition characterized by an abnormal increase in the thickness of the choroid, which may be associated with various ocular or systemic conditions. Choroid thickening can be measured using imaging techniques such as optical coherence tomography (OCT).
Choroid thickening

A condition characterized by accumulation of fluid within the corneal epithelium, leading to swelling, blurred vision, and discomfort. It is often associated with increased intraocular pressure, endothelial dysfunction, or contact lens overuse. Clinical features may include a hazy cornea and microcystic changes visible on slit-lamp examination.
Corneal epithelial edema

bnormal blood vessels in the retina that form as a response to vascular occlusion, serving as bypass channels to redirect blood flow around obstructed or damaged retinal vessels. Retinal shunt vessels are often associated with conditions like retinal vein occlusion or diabetic retinopathy and may appear as tortuous or dilated vessels on fundoscopic examination.
Retinal shunt vessels

A condition characterized by the formation of filaments composed of degenerated epithelial cells and mucus attached to the corneal surface. It is associated with symptoms such as pain, foreign body sensation, photophobia, and tearing. Filamentary keratitis is often linked to underlying conditions such as dry eye disease, post-surgical ocular surface disorders, or systemic diseases like Sjoegren syndrome.
Filamentary keratitis
Concentration of D-glucosylsphingosine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating glucosylsphingosine concentration
A condition characterized by bleeding at or near the optic disc, visible as a flame-shaped or splinter hemorrhage on fundoscopic examination.
Optic disc hemorrhage
The concentration of progranulin in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating progranulin concentration
Enlargement of one or more lymph nodes located in front of the ear.
Preauricular lymphadenopathy
Growth of nail tissue outside the ungual plate, generally in the finger.
Onychoheterotopia

A deviation from the normal level of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules expressed at the cell surface. The cell-mediated adaptive immune response is regulated by the MHC, which is called human leukocyte antigen (HLA) in humans. HLA molecules are cell surface glycoproteins whose primary function is to present endogenous and exogenous antigens to T lymphocytes for recognition and response. The HLA molecules that present antigen to T lymphocytes are divided into two main classes: HLA class I and HLA class II molecules.
Abnormal MHC surface expression
Flexion MRI (imaging with neutral and flexed about 30-40 degrees neck position) reveals an anterior shift of the cervical dural sac from the lamina in the region of C4 to C7.
Forward displacement of posterior cervical dura mater on neck flexion

A localized area of corneal thinning typically occurring adjacent to an elevated lesion, such as a conjunctival scar, pterygium, or poorly fitting contact lens. Corneal dellen result from tear film instability and localized dehydration. Without timely treatment, they may progress to epithelial defects or corneal ulceration.
Corneal dellen

A condition characterized by dryness of the conjunctiva, often associated with keratinization of the conjunctival epithelium. Conjunctival xerosis is commonly linked to vitamin A deficiency, severe dry eye disease, or systemic conditions such as Sjogren syndrome. Clinical features may include a dull, rough conjunctival surface and reduced mucosal secretions.
Conjunctival xerosis
Difficulty rotating the lower part of the arm away from the body (tested with the elbow flexed and the elbow held next to the side of the body) secondary to pain, weakness, or mechanical block.
Limited shoulder external rotation

A history of exposure to repeated hand trauma as observed with occupations in which use of hands is frequent such as construction, food preparation and serving related occupations, and transportation and material moving occupations.
Occupational exposure to frequent hand trauma
An inability to fully extend the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joint of a finger (extension of an MCP joint straightens the finger).
Inability to fully extend finger at metacarpophalangeal joint
Inflammation of the wrist joint.
Wrist arthritis
Widening of the space between the scaphoid and lunate on x-ray; scapholunate dissociation.
Scapholunate interval widening

Applies to an abnormality whose distribution is limited to or predominantly affects the fleshy mass on the volar (palmar) aspect of the digit, distal to the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint (known as the pulp of the finger).
FInger pulp localization
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the ulnar side of the wrist.
Ulnar wrist pain
Radiographic widening of the space between the lunate and triquetrum bones.
Lunotriquetral interval widening
Anteroposterior wrist radiograph showing ulnar translocation of the carpus from the distal radius with widening of the radial styloid-scaphoid space.
Ulnar translocation of the carpus
A popping or snapping sensation (noise or feeling) at the time of an injury.
Snapping sensation at time of injury

Pagetoid spread connotes the spread of single neoplastic cells, and small nests of them above the basal layer in a variety of melanocytic and nonmelanocytic neoplasms similar to the pattern seen in Paget's and in extramammary Paget disease.
Pagetoid spread
Central scarring of skin lesions.
Central scarring

A breakage (partial or complete tear) of the scapholunate ligament. The most common cause is physical trauma to the wrist such as a fall onto an outstretched hand. Tear of the scapholunate ligament may lead to carpal instability.
Scapholunate ligament tear

A breakage (partial or complete tear) of the lunotriquetral ligament. The most common cause is physical trauma to the wrist such as a fall onto an outstretched hand. Rupture or tear of the the lunotriquetral ligament may lead to carpal instability.
Lunotriquetral ligament tear
Arthritis at the pisotriquetral joint. Radiographic evidence of arthritis at the pisotriquetral joint includes joint space narrowing, osteophytes, subchondral cysts, and/or subchondral sclerosis.
Pisotriquetral arthritis
A type of carpal instability characterized by volar tilt of the lunate bone.
Volar intercalated segment instability
Any substantial discrepancy between the measurement of oxygen saturation with finger probe pulse oximetry as compared to an arterial blood gas, which is considered the gold standard.
Inaccurate finger pulse oximetry oxygen saturation measurement
Inaccurately reduced oxygen saturation as measured by finger or toe pulse oximetry compared to oxygen saturation as measured by venous or arterial blood gas analysis.
Finger pulse oximetry lower than arterial blood gas analysis measurement of oxygen saturation
Inaccurately elevated oxygen saturation as measured by finger or toe pulse oximetry compared to oxygen saturation as measured by venous or arterial blood gas analysis.
Finger pulse oximetry higher than arterial blood gas analysis measurement of oxygen saturation

Thumb sucking is a behavior that ceases spontaneously in most children between 2 and 4 years of age. If thumb sucking continues, negative consequences can occur, such as a deformity of the nail or paronychia. This term refers to a history of habitual thumb sucking past the age of 4 years of life.
History of thumb sucking past the age of four years

Skin inflammatory reaction triggered by a wide variety of stimuli, including infections, foreign bodies, malignancy, metabolites, and chemicals. From a pathogenic point of view, they are divided into non-infectious and infectious granulomas. From a clinical point of view, it is useful to divide cutaneous granulomatosis into localized and more disseminated forms, although this distinction can be sometimes artificial.
Cutaneous granulomatosis
Obstruction of urine flow through one or both ureters caused by issues such as injury, infection, tumours and surgery.
Ureteric stricture

A retinal vascular abnormality characterized by indentation or compression of a retinal vein at an arteriovenous crossing, leading to changes in venous caliber. AV crossing signs are commonly associated with hypertensive retinopathy and may contribute to retinal vein occlusion. They are indicative of vascular remodeling due to chronic hypertension or other systemic vascular diseases.
Arteriovenous crossing sign

Curvilinear or circumferential breaks in Descemet membrane, typically associated with congenital glaucoma. Haab striae result from elevated intraocular pressure during corneal development, leading to the formation of horizontal or arcuate lines that may be visible on slit-lamp examination. They can contribute to corneal astigmatism and visual impairment.
Haab striae
Growth of Legionella bacteria in a sputum culture.
Positive Legionella sputum culture
Streptococcus pneumoniae growth in sputum culture.
Positive Streptococcus pneumoniae sputum culture
Demonstration of Blastomyces dermatitidis by microscopic examination of a stained sputum specimen.
Positive Blastomyces dermatitidis sputum fungal stain
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the posterior (back) part of the shoulder.
Posterior shoulder pain

An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the superior or proximal aspect of the shoulder over the acromion, distal clavicle, and/or acromioclavicular (AC) joint.
Superior shoulder pain
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the localized aspect (on the side) of the shoulder.
Lateral shoulder pain
Subjective or objective feeling of clunking/clicking in the shoulder with movement, shoulder 'giving way', or sensation of shoulder dislocating.
Shoulder instability
A injury with a team (rip, split, or disruption) to the labrum, which is the ring of cartilage that surrounds the socket of the shoulder joint (the glenoid).
Shoulder labrum tear

Sensation of a pain with or without clicking or clunking sensation with the following test. Flex patients elbow to 90 degrees and abduct the arm 120 degrees while maximally externally rotating the arm, then examiner lowers the arm to 60 degrees of abduction. A positive test occurs with pain and/or a painful click along the posterior joint line between 120 degrees and 90 degrees of abduction.
Positive modified dynamic labral shear test

Pain in shoulder reproduced when examiner applies downward pressure on the arm while patient resists pressure in the following position: elbow extended, shoulder forward flexed to 90 degrees and 10-15 degrees adducted with palm facing down. This can be compared to the same position but with the palm facing up which should be less painful.
Positive O'Brien active compression test

The individual being investigated displays noticeable apprehension (unease) during a test for shoulder instability in which the individual is laying supine with shoulder abducted to 90 degrees, elbow flexed to 90 degrees, and an external rotation pressure with combined downward pressure is applied on the upper arm.
Positive shoulder apprehension test
A condition characterized by the presence of foam or bubbles within the tear film, often associated with meibomian gland dysfunction or ocular surface diseases.
Foamy tear film
The formation of large, bluish, nodular lesions in the superficial corneal stroma, often associated with chronic keratitis or aging. These nodules may lead to visual impairment.
Salzmann corneal nodules

The abnormal growth of blood vessels into the corneal stroma, often associated with ocular herpes, chronic inflammation, infection, or hypoxia. This condition can lead to corneal scarring and vision impairment.
Corneal stromal vascularisation
Linear or arcuate deposition of iron within the corneal epithelium or stroma, typically associated with conditions such as keratoconus, corneal degeneration, or postsurgical corneal changes.
Corneal iron line
A condition characterized by redundant, loose conjunctival tissue, typically located between the globe and the lower eyelid, which may cause ocular discomfort, tear film instability, or epiphora.
Conjunctivochalasis

Increased pigmentation of the conjunctiva, characterized by brown or black discoloration due to melanocytic proliferation or pigment deposition. It may be associated with benign conditions such as primary acquired melanosis or malignant transformation into conjunctival melanoma.
Conjunctival hyperpigmentation
Antibodies against antigens presented by the cell wall of the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Anti-Saccharomyces cerevisiae antibodies

The fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO) is elevated above the upper limit of normal. FeNO is an endogenous gaseous molecule which can be measured in the human breath test because of airway inflammation. It has been studied extensively as a marker of inflammation and has been incorporated into an algorithm for asthma management.
Elevated fraction exhaled nitric oxide

A condition characterized by increased blood flow and congestion of the iris vasculature, leading to a reddish discoloration of the iris. Iris hyperemia is commonly associated with anterior uveitis, angle-closure glaucoma, or ocular inflammation.
Iris hyperemia
The number of reticulated platelets per volume of blood in the peripheral circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating reticulated platelet count
The number of reticulated platelets per volume of blood in the peripheral circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating reticulated platelet count
The number of reticulated platelets per volume of blood in the peripheral circulation is outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal circulating reticulated platelet count

A sign that can be observed in diseases such as Pyogenic or suppurative flexor tenosynovitis in which the affected finger is held in a flexed position. Often, there is pain on any attempt at passive finger extension. This finding is to be distinguished from a contracture of a finger joint in which the flexed positions is fixed.
Flexed posturing of finger

Elevation of the the alpha-defensin concentration in synovial aspirate is above the upper limit of normal. The alpha-defensin test is a qualitative immunoassay optimized and validated for synovial fluid. The alpha-defensin protein is an antimicrobial peptide that is naturally released by neutrophils responding to a pathogen in the synovial fluid.
Positive synovial fluid alpha-defensin
Salter-Harris fractures (physeal fractures) refer to fractures through a growth plate (physis) and are, therefore, specifically applied to bone fractures in children.
Physeal fracture

A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture in which the fracture line extends through the physis or within the growth plate. Type I fractures are due to the longitudinal force applied through the physis, which splits the epiphysis from the metaphysis.
Salter I fracture

A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture in which the fracture extends through both the physis and metaphysis. These are most common and occur away from the joint space. When the small corner of the metaphysis is visible, this is known as a corner sign or Thurston-Holland fragment.
Salter II fracture
A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture in which the fracture is intra-articular and extends from the physis into the epiphysis.
Salter III fracture
A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture in which the fracture is intra-articular and passes through the epiphysis, physis, and metaphysis.
Salter IV fracture

A type of physeal (Salter-Harris) fracture that is due to a crush or compression injury of the growth plate. In type V, the force is transmitted through the epiphysis and physis, potentially disrupting the germinal matrix, hypertrophic region, and vascular supply.
Salter V fracture
A cut or injury to the soft tissue under the fingernail or toenail.
Nail bed laceration
Recent or remote history of distal radius fracture of the symptomatic arm.
History of distal radius fracture

Recent or remote history of a tear in the triangular fibrocartilage complex (TFCC). The TFCC is a load-bearing structure between the lunate, triquetrum, and ulnar head. The function of the TFCC is to act as a stabilizer for the ulnar aspect of the wrist. The TFCC is at risk for either acute or chronic degenerative injury.
History of triangular fibrocartilage complex tear
The creases (wrinkles) on the soles of the feet are less pronounced than normal, or absent.
Reduced plantar creases
Damage to the skin and underlying tissues caused by an agents such as heat, chemicals, electricity, radiation, or friction, resulting in pain, redness, swelling, and sometimes blisters or charring.
Skin burn
The concentration of carboxysterols in lymphoblastoid cells cultured in cholesterol-depleted medium is below the lower limit of normal.
Elevanted carboxysterol concentration in cultured lymphoblasts

An anomaly that can be ascertained by iron-specific magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) sequences such as gradient-echo (GRE) and susceptibility-weighted imaging (SWI). Superficial siderosis of the central nervous system is a chronic condition due to persistent or repeated long-term bleeding into the subarachnoid space, leading to subpial hemosiderin deposition. Hemosiderin deposition on MRI is seen as a T2 hypointensity and preferentially outlines the cerebellum and brainstem surface.
Superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition

A type of superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition that most commonly occurs due to iron deposits in the superficial cortical layers following bleeding from leptomeningeal vessels, most often from cerebral amyloid angiopathy in patients aged 55 or older.
Cortical superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition

A type of superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition that involves the cerebellum and brainstem, most commonly the superior vermis, quadrigeminal plate, and basal cerebral surfaces. Cerebellar atrophy, particularly the superior vermis and anterior cerebellar hemispheres, can also be seen on a computed tomography scan of the head. The MRI of the spinal cord may reveal myelomalacia, syringomyelia, owl-eyes, or snake-eyes signs. The most common etiology for classic or primary infratentorial superficial siderosis is spinal dural defects, often dural tears.
Infratentorial superficial CNS hemosiderin deposition

Pulmonary Hyperplasia is an absolute increase in the number of alveoli, which are mildly enlarged. Pulmonary hyperplasia has been also referred to as polyalveolar lobe and type 3 cystic adenomatoid malformation.
Pulmonary hyperplasia
Demonstration of protozoan parasites in a cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) specimen by microscopy.
Positive protozoan parasite CSF wet mount test

A gallbladder (GB) polyp is a growth that projects from the lining of the inside wall of the gallbladder into the lumen of the GB. GB polyps are a common incidental sonographic finding, the vast majority of which are benign.
Gallbladder polyp
Multiple polyps arising from the gallbladder mucosal wall.
Gallbladder polyposis
Discontinuity of the biceps tendon as observed by ultrasound or magnetic resonance (MR) imaging.
Biceps tendon rupture

Medial epicondyle apophysitis (MEA), also known as little league elbow, is an overuse injury prevalent among adolescent athletes whose sport involves repetitive overhand throwing, racket use, or other overhead arm motions. The medial epicondyle is a bony protrusion on the medial elbow with its own ossification center, separate from the main distal humeral physis, known as an apophysis. Medial epicondyle apophysitis occurs due to excessive and repetitive valgus stress placed on the apophysis before its closure. Over time, the repetitive strain results in a traction-type injury and may cause pathologic widening and inflammation of the apophysis or even an avulsion fracture.
Medial epicondyle apophysitis

A partial (subluxation) loss of alignment at the base of the thumb, where the first metacarpal bone meets the trapezium bone of the wrist. Thumb radiographs showing carpometacarpal (CMC) joint space widening and/or incongruity of the joint space between thumb metacarpal bone and the trapezium bone.
Thumb carpometacarpal subluxation

A descriptor indicating that a condition, lesion, or abnormality is confined to the lower eyelid. This localization may be relevant for various ocular conditions, including infections, structural abnormalities, or dermatological diseases affecting the lower eyelid region.
Localized to the lower eyelid
Applies to an abnormality that is situated in an eyelid.
Localized to eyelid

A visual phenomenon characterized by the perception of bright rings or halos surrounding light sources. Halo vision is often associated with optical irregularities such as corneal edema, cataracts, or intraocular lens complications. It may also occur in conditions affecting the tear film or due to the presence of glare from light scattering within the ocular media.
Halo vision
The presence of blood in the seminal fluid.
Hematospermia
Choledocholithiasis is the presence of stones within the common bile duct.
Choledocholithiasis
Paresthesias on the lateral aspect of the shoulder and upper arm. Weakness in shoulder abduction (deltoid) and shoulder external rotation (teres minor).
Axillary nerve distribution

X-ray of the pelvis (AP, inlet, and outlet views) showing fracture of the pelvic ring, including iliac wing (ilium), superior or inferior pubic ramus, or ischium, and/or displacement of the pubic symphysis or sacroiliac joints.
Pelvic ring fracture

An injury consisting of a laterally displaced scapula with separation of the ipsilateral acromioclavicular joint, disruption of the ipsilateral subclavian vessels and brachial plexus, and an intact overlying skin.
Scapulothoracic dissociation
Refers to pain that is worse when the individual bears weight with the affected body part.
Pain exacerbated by weight bearing
The distal phalanx of the adducted thumb extends beyond the ulnar border of the palm (The thumb protrudes from the clenched fist).
Thumb sign

Partial or complete breakage (rupture) of the tibialis anterior tendon (TAT). The TAT is the principal dorsiflexor of the ankle joint and secondary invertor of the foot. It has important roles in the different stages of gait; in the swing phase, it concentrically dorsiflex the ankle for foot clearance and during plantarflexion of the ankle in the stance phase, it eccentrically contract to stabilize the ankle and prevent damage to the foot and ankle. Clinically, presentations in acute lacerations or direct trauma cases are straight forward, in chronic and atraumatic cases usually the symptoms at the time of TAT rupture are more subtle. Other manifestations include mild pain, localized mass, palpable gap, loss of strength, instability during gait, gait disturbances with forefoot dropping and stumbling and high stepping gait.
Tibialis anterior tendon rupture
Activity of the enzyme von Willebrand factor-cleaving protease (ADAMTS13) in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating ADAMTS13 activity
An abnormal result of the methacholine challenge test, which is a bronchoprovocation technique used to evaluate airway hyperresponsiveness, particularly in patients with suspected asthma.
Abnormal methacholine challenge test
inheres in
inheres in part of
